{"title_page": "Kraftklub", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Kraftklub\n| image               = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = In Schwarz\n| origin              = [[Chemnitz]], [[Germany]]\n| genre               = [[Indie rock]], [[punk rock]], [[rap rock]], [[garage rock]], [[post-punk revival]]\n| years_active        = 2010&ndash;present\n| label               = [[Vertigo Records]]\n| associated_acts     =\n| website             = [http://www.kraftklub.to]\n| current_members     = Felix Brummer <small>(Felix Kummer)</small> <br />Karl Schumann <br />Till Brummer <small>(Till Kummer)</small><br />Steffen Israel <small>(Steffen Thiede)</small><br />Max Marschk}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n'''Kraftklub''' is a five-person band from [[Chemnitz]], [[Germany]]. Their music combines [[rock music|rock]] / [[indie rock|indie]] and [[Sprechgesang]] with German lyrics and is generally considered to be a mixture of [[rap]] and [[indie rock|indie]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visions.de/live/tournee/16818/Kraftklub |title=VISIONS empfiehlt: Kraftklub |language=de |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512223812/http://www.visions.de/live/tournee/16818/kraftklub |archivedate=12 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n===Founding and early years (2009\u20132011)===\nThe band members first met at school <ref name=\"reflect\">{{cite web |url=http://www.reflect.de/2011/12/kraftklub-interview-%E2%80%9Emicky-maus-ist-ein-bloder-kleiner-klugscheiser%E2%80%9C/ |title=Kraftklub-Interview: \"Micky Maus ist ein bl\u00f6der, kleiner Klugschei\u00dfer!\" |language=de |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520203538/http://www.reflect.de/2011/12/kraftklub-interview-%E2%80%9Emicky-maus-ist-ein-bloder-kleiner-klugscheiser%E2%80%9C/ |archivedate=20 May 2012 }}</ref> and founded the band at the end of 2009.<ref name=\"reflect\"/> At the [[Splash! (festival)|Splash Festival]] 2009, rapper Bernd Bass (Felix Brummer) performed together with the rock band ''Neon Blocks'' for the first time. At the end of 2009, they founded the band Kraftklub and started recording their first studio album. On 13 February 2010, they released their first EP, titled ''Adonis Maximus'' at a record release party in the Chemnitz club Atomino.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atomino-club.de/contrexx/index.php?section=calendar&catid=0&yearID=2010&monthID=2 |title=RAMBA ZAMBA pres. KRAFTKLUB RECORD RELEASE |language=de |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109054250/http://www.atomino-club.de/contrexx/index.php?section=calendar&catid=0&yearID=2010&monthID=2 |archivedate=9 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, the band won the ''New Music Award'', a music prize awarded by various [[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]] radio stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://on3.de/element/6800/new-music-award-2010-kraftklub-raeumen-ab#/element/6800/new-music-award-2010-kraftklub-raeumen-ab |title=New Music Award 2010 Kraftklub r\u00e4umen ab |language=de |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110829051244/http://on3.de/element/6800/new-music-award-2010-kraftklub-raeumen-ab |archivedate=29 August 2011 }}</ref> As a result, several major labels became aware of them. As of January 2011, they are signed to Universal Domestic Rock/Vertigo Berlin.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universal-music.de/kraftklub/news/detail/article:164867/neu-kraftklub-bei-vertigo-berlin |title=Neu! Kraftklub bei Vertigo Berlin! |publisher=[[Universal Music]] |language=de |accessdate=2014-12-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617033304/http://www.universal-music.de/kraftklub/news/detail/article:164867/neu-kraftklub-bei-vertigo-berlin |archive-date=17 June 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musikmarkt.de/Aktuell/News/Universal-Domestic-Rock-angelt-sich-Newcomer-Band-Kraftklub |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120804224237/http://www.musikmarkt.de/Aktuell/News/Universal-Domestic-Rock-angelt-sich-Newcomer-Band-Kraftklub |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-08-04 |title=Universal Domestic Rock angelt sich Newcomer-Band Kraftklub |website=musikmarkt.de |language=de |accessdate=2014-12-01 }}</ref>\n\nKraftklub have performed as the support act for bands including [[Beatsteaks]], [[Fettes Brot]], [[Casper (rapper)|Casper]], [[Die Toten Hosen]], and [[Rammstein]].<ref name=\"reflect\" /> On 5 August 2011, they released their first single, ''Zu Jung''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universal-music.de/kraftklub/diskografie/detail/product:179460/zu-jung |title=KRAFTKLUB - Zu Jung - Diskografie |publisher=[[Universal Music]] |language=de |accessdate=2014-12-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120124143856/http://www.universal-music.de/kraftklub/diskografie/detail/product:179460/zu-jung |archive-date=24 January 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\n=== Breakthrough with ''Mit K'' (2011\u20132013) ===\n[[File:Kraftklub-2.jpg|thumb|Kraftklub at Melt! Festival 2013]]\nOn 29 September 2011, the band represented [[Saxony]] in the [[Bundesvision Song Contest]] with their song ''Ich will nicht nach Berlin'', coming fifth with a total of 89&nbsp;points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvtotal.prosieben.de/tvtotal/specials/bundesvision2011/index.html |title=Bundesvision2011 |language=de |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512175713/http://tvtotal.prosieben.de/tvtotal/specials/bundesvision2011/index.html |archivedate=12 May 2012 }}</ref> The single was released the next day where it reached number 45 on the German [[Media Control Charts]].<ref name=\"acharts\">{{cite web |url=http://acharts.us/album/68262 |title=Kraftklub - Mit K - Music Charts |website=acharts.us |accessdate=2014-12-01}}</ref> Their debut album ''Mit K'' was released on 20 January 2012 and shot straight to number one in Germany.<ref name=\"acharts\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freiepresse.de/NACHRICHTEN/TOP-THEMA/Kraftklub-startet-durch-Album-Mit-K-von-0-auf-1-in-den-Charts-artikel7891041.php |title=Kraftklub startet durch: Album \"Mit K\" von 0 auf 1 in den Charts |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120416100710/http://www.freiepresse.de/NACHRICHTEN/TOP-THEMA/Kraftklub-startet-durch-Album-Mit-K-von-0-auf-1-in-den-Charts-artikel7891041.php |archivedate=16 April 2012 }}</ref> In April 2012, ''Songs f\u00fcr Liam'', the next single from their album, was released. It debuted at number 40 and peaked at number 14 in the German Media Control Charts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://acharts.us/song/69538 |title=Kraftclub - Songs F\u00fcr Liam - Music Charts |website=acharts.us |accessdate=2014-12-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 2012,  [[K.I.Z.]] and Kraftklub gave an unannounced concert on the roof of the Chemnitz commercial complex ''Terminal 3'' as part of the documentary film series ''Durch die Nacht mit...'' commissioned by [[Arte|ARTE]]. The performance was announced only a few hours before via social networks, despite the ban on dancing on Good Friday, and as a result of the crowds of spectators the police closed off the Chemnitzer Br\u00fcckenstra\u00dfe. <ref>Florian Harlass: [http://www.371stadtmagazin.de/371magazin/items/Kraftklub-Jahresrueckblick-felixkummer-chemnitz-2012-Zuhause-371.html ''Jahresr\u00fcckblick mit K \u2013 Kraftklub 2012'']. 371stadtmagazin.de</ref>\n\nKraftklub refer to their hometown of [[Chemnitz]] as \"Karl-Marx-Stadt\" <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.laut.de/Kraftklub |title=laut.de-Biographie - Kraftklub |website=laut.de |language=de |accessdate=2014-12-01}}</ref> (this was the name the city was known as from 1953 to 1990) - one of their songs on ''Mit K'' is entitled ''Karl-Marx-Stadt'' - and they are known for their trademark poloshirts, varsity jackets and [[suspenders]].<ref name=\"reflect\" />\n\nFor [[Record Store Day]] 2012, Kraftklub released the song ''Songs for Liam'' in a version with [[Casper (rapper)|Casper]] as vinyl single, which is limited to 700 pieces. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/KraftKlub-Feat-Casper-Songs-F%C3%BCr-Liam/release/3555694|title=Kraftklub feat. Casper - Songs f\u00fcr Liam (2012)|last=|first=|date=|website=discogs.com|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIts first concert outside of Germany was at 19 September 2012, in \"La Puerta Grande\" Bar in [[Bogot\u00e1]], thanks to the \"Kolumbien mit K\" tour promoted by the Goethe Institut - Colombia, which took them by Bogot\u00e1, [[Medell\u00edn]] and [[Cali]], each one with two concerts respectively, and one in Cartagena.{{citation needed |date=December 2014}}\n\nIn 2013, Kraftklub was nominated (among others) together with the group [[Frei.Wild]] for the ''music award Echo'' in the category ''Rock/Alternative National''. On 6 Mrach 2013, Kraftklub announced that they want to be removed from the list of nominees, as Kraftklub does not want to be named in the same line as FreiWild. After [[MIA.|Mia.]] and [[Die \u00c4rzte]] also withdrew their participation, Frei.Wild was removed from the list of nominees and Kraftklub received the \"Kritikerpreis National\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ok-magazin.de/entertainment/musik/16855/kraftklub-freuen-sich-nach-nominierten-eklat-ueber-echo-|title=Kraftklub wins 'Echo' after nomination scandel|last=|first=|date=20 March 2013|website=ok-magazin.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe song ''Eure M\u00e4dchen'' can be heard on the soundtrack of the PC and console game [[FIFA 13]]. It is the only German title in the game. Kraftklub has a guest appearance in the song ''Ganz sch\u00f6n okay'' on the album ''Hinterland'' by German rapper Casper.\n\n=== In Schwarz (2014\u20132016) ===\n[[File:Kraftklub (172).JPG|thumb|Kraftklub at Openin Festival 2014]]\n[[File:Kraftklub, Kosmonaut Festival.jpg|thumb|Kraftklub at Kosmonaut Festival 2014]]\nOn 20 May 2014, the music video ''Hand in Hand'' (in a version with bassist Till Brummer on vocals) of an allegedly new band called ''In Schwarz'' appeared on [[YouTube]]. The video was uploaded by the music label ''[[Audiolith Records]]''. <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6FzA3o9aXrQ</ref> On 2 June 2014, ''In Schwarz'' appeared on the German television show ''Circus HalliGalli'' and revealed themselves as Kraftklub.\n\nOn 20 November 2015, the first live album ''Randale'' was released. Part of the DVD is a recording of the concert in the [[Max-Schmeling-Halle]] in Berlin from 6. March 2015. In January 2016 followed the ''Randale''-tour, in which the band gave concerts in several German cities. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musikexpress.de/kraftklub-hauen-live-dvd-raus-und-gehen-auf-randale-tour-409669/|title=Kraftklub releases new live DVD and goes on tour|last=|first=|date=|website=musikexpress.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Keine Nacht f\u00fcr Niemanden (2017\u2013present) ===\nOn 16 March 2017, the band they released the first single ''Dein Lied'' from the subsequently announced album ''Keine Nacht f\u00fcr Niemand'' during a 10-hour Facebook livestream, which was released on 2 June 2017. The title of the album is an allusion to the album ''Keine Macht f\u00fcr Niemand'' by the band [[Ton Steine Scherben]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.de/kraftklub-album-keine-nacht-fuer-niemand-im-juni-2017-1216323/|title=Kraftklub's new album \"Keine Nacht f\u00fcr Niemand\" to be published in June 2017|last=|first=|date=20 March 2017|website=rollingstone.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n* 2012: ''Mit K''\n* 2014: ''In Schwarz''\n* 2015: ''Randale'' (live album)\n* 2017: ''Keine Nacht f\u00fcr Niemand''\n\n===EPs===\n* 2010: ''Adonis Maximus''\n* 2012: ''Live im Astra Berlin''\n* 2012: ''Songs f\u00fcr Liam''\n\n===Singles===\n* 2011: \"Zu jung\"\n* 2011: \"Ich will nicht nach Berlin\"\n* 2011: \"Eure M\u00e4dchen\"\n* 2012: \"Songs f\u00fcr Liam\"\n* 2012: \"Kein Liebeslied\"\n* 2012: \"Mein Leben\"\n* 2014: \"Hand in Hand\"\n* 2014: \"Unsere Fans\"\n* 2014: \"Wie ich\"\n* 2014: \"Sch\u00fcsse in die Luft\"\n* 2015: \"Blau\"\n* 2015: \"Alles wegen Dir\"\n* 2017: \"Dein Lied\"\n* 2017: \"Fenster\"\n* 2017: \"Sklave\"\n* 2017: \"Chemie Chemie Ya\"\n* 2017: \"Am Ende\"\n* 2018: \"Liebe zu Dritt\"\n\n==Band members==\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:2015 RiP Kraftklub - Felix Brummer by 2eight - 8SC3231.jpg|Felix Brummer (Rap, vocals) in 2015\nFile:2017 RiP - Kraftklub - Karl Schumann - by 2eight - DSC8513.jpg|Karl Schumann (Rhythm guitar, vocals) in 2017\nFile:2015 RiP Kraftklub - Till Brummer by 2eight - 8SC3240.jpg|Till Brummer (Bass) in 2015\nFile:2015 RiP Kraftklub - Steffen Isreal by 2eight - 8SC3355.jpg|Steffen Israel (Lead guitar, keys) in 2015\nFile:2015 RiP Kraftklub - Max Marschk by 2eight - 8SC3298.jpg|Max Marschk (Drums) in 2015\n</gallery>Till and Felix are brothers <ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvtotal.prosieben.de/tvtotal/videos/player/index.html?contentId=122386&initialTab=related|title=Kraftklub mit \"K\" (Event vom 29.09.2011)|language=de|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428173345/http://tvtotal.prosieben.de/tvtotal/videos/player/index.html?contentId=122386&initialTab=related|archivedate=28 April 2012|accessdate=13 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"reflect\" /> and the sons of ''AG. Geige'' member Jan Kummer. Since there is no artistic connection to Kraftklub, the brothers use the surname Brummer instead.\n\n==Song appearances==\n* \"Eure M\u00e4dchen\" from [[EA Sports]]' ''[[FIFA 13]]'' Soundtrack (2012)\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://www.kraftklub.to/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:German rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Participants in the Bundesvision Song Contest]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Kraftklub\n| image               = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = In Schwarz\n| origin              = [[Chemnitz]], [[Germany]]\n| genre               = [[Indie rock]], [[punk rock]], [[rap rock]], [[garage rock]], [[post-punk revival]]\n| years_active        = 2010&ndash;present\n| label               = [[Vertigo Records]]\n| associated_acts     =\n| website             = [http://www.kraftklub.to]\n| current_members     = Felix Brummer <small>(Felix Kummer)</small> <br />Karl Schumann <br />Till Brummer <small>(Till Kummer)</small><br />Steffen Israel <small>(Steffen Thiede)</small><br />Max Marschk}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n'''Kraftklub''' is a five-person band from [[Chemnitz]], [[Germany]]. Their music combines [[rock music|rock]] / [[indie rock|indie]] and [[Sprechgesang]] with German lyrics and is generally considered to be a mixture of [[rap]] and [[indie rock|indie]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visions.de/live/tournee/16818/Kraftklub |title=VISIONS empfiehlt: Kraftklub |language=de |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512223812/http://www.visions.de/live/tournee/16818/kraftklub |archivedate=12 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n===Founding and early years (2009\u20132011)===\n[[File:Kraftklub-2.jpg|thumb|Kraftklub at Melt! Festival 2013]]\n[[File:Kraftklub (172).JPG|thumb|Kraftklub at Openin Festival 2014]]\n[[File:Kraftklub, Kosmonaut Festival.jpg|thumb|Kraftklub at Kosmonaut Festival 2014]]\nThe band members first met at school <ref name=\"reflect\">{{cite web |url=http://www.reflect.de/2011/12/kraftklub-interview-%E2%80%9Emicky-maus-ist-ein-bloder-kleiner-klugscheiser%E2%80%9C/ |title=Kraftklub-Interview: \"Micky Maus ist ein bl\u00f6der, kleiner Klugschei\u00dfer!\" |language=de |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520203538/http://www.reflect.de/2011/12/kraftklub-interview-%E2%80%9Emicky-maus-ist-ein-bloder-kleiner-klugscheiser%E2%80%9C/ |archivedate=20 May 2012 }}</ref> and founded the band at the end of 2009.<ref name=\"reflect\"/> At the [[Splash! (festival)|Splash Festival]] 2009, rapper Bernd Bass (Felix Brummer) performed together with the rock band ''Neon Blocks'' for the first time. At the end of 2009, they founded the band Kraftklub and started recording their first studio album. On 13 February 2010, they released their first EP, titled ''Adonis Maximus'' at a record release party in the Chemnitz club Atomino.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atomino-club.de/contrexx/index.php?section=calendar&catid=0&yearID=2010&monthID=2 |title=RAMBA ZAMBA pres. KRAFTKLUB RECORD RELEASE |language=de |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109054250/http://www.atomino-club.de/contrexx/index.php?section=calendar&catid=0&yearID=2010&monthID=2 |archivedate=9 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, the band won the ''New Music Award'', a music prize awarded by various [[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]] radio stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://on3.de/element/6800/new-music-award-2010-kraftklub-raeumen-ab#/element/6800/new-music-award-2010-kraftklub-raeumen-ab |title=New Music Award 2010 Kraftklub r\u00e4umen ab |language=de |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110829051244/http://on3.de/element/6800/new-music-award-2010-kraftklub-raeumen-ab |archivedate=29 August 2011 }}</ref> As a result, several major labels became aware of them. As of January 2011, they are signed to Universal Domestic Rock/Vertigo Berlin.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universal-music.de/kraftklub/news/detail/article:164867/neu-kraftklub-bei-vertigo-berlin |title=Neu! Kraftklub bei Vertigo Berlin! |publisher=[[Universal Music]] |language=de |accessdate=2014-12-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617033304/http://www.universal-music.de/kraftklub/news/detail/article:164867/neu-kraftklub-bei-vertigo-berlin |archive-date=17 June 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musikmarkt.de/Aktuell/News/Universal-Domestic-Rock-angelt-sich-Newcomer-Band-Kraftklub |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120804224237/http://www.musikmarkt.de/Aktuell/News/Universal-Domestic-Rock-angelt-sich-Newcomer-Band-Kraftklub |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-08-04 |title=Universal Domestic Rock angelt sich Newcomer-Band Kraftklub |website=musikmarkt.de |language=de |accessdate=2014-12-01 }}</ref>\n\nKraftklub have performed as the support act for bands including [[Beatsteaks]], [[Fettes Brot]], [[Casper (rapper)|Casper]], [[Die Toten Hosen]], and [[Rammstein]].<ref name=\"reflect\" /> On 5 August 2011, they released their first single, ''Zu Jung''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universal-music.de/kraftklub/diskografie/detail/product:179460/zu-jung |title=KRAFTKLUB - Zu Jung - Diskografie |publisher=[[Universal Music]] |language=de |accessdate=2014-12-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120124143856/http://www.universal-music.de/kraftklub/diskografie/detail/product:179460/zu-jung |archive-date=24 January 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\n=== Breakthrough with ''Mit K'' (2011\u20132013) ===\nOn 29 September 2011, the band represented [[Saxony]] in the [[Bundesvision Song Contest]] with their song ''Ich will nicht nach Berlin'', coming fifth with a total of 89&nbsp;points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvtotal.prosieben.de/tvtotal/specials/bundesvision2011/index.html |title=Bundesvision2011 |language=de |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512175713/http://tvtotal.prosieben.de/tvtotal/specials/bundesvision2011/index.html |archivedate=12 May 2012 }}</ref> The single was released the next day where it reached number 45 on the German [[Media Control Charts]].<ref name=\"acharts\">{{cite web |url=http://acharts.us/album/68262 |title=Kraftklub - Mit K - Music Charts |website=acharts.us |accessdate=2014-12-01}}</ref> Their debut album ''Mit K'' was released on 20 January 2012 and shot straight to number one in Germany.<ref name=\"acharts\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freiepresse.de/NACHRICHTEN/TOP-THEMA/Kraftklub-startet-durch-Album-Mit-K-von-0-auf-1-in-den-Charts-artikel7891041.php |title=Kraftklub startet durch: Album \"Mit K\" von 0 auf 1 in den Charts |accessdate=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120416100710/http://www.freiepresse.de/NACHRICHTEN/TOP-THEMA/Kraftklub-startet-durch-Album-Mit-K-von-0-auf-1-in-den-Charts-artikel7891041.php |archivedate=16 April 2012 }}</ref> In April 2012, ''Songs f\u00fcr Liam'', the next single from their album, was released. It debuted at number 40 and peaked at number 14 in the German Media Control Charts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://acharts.us/song/69538 |title=Kraftclub - Songs F\u00fcr Liam - Music Charts |website=acharts.us |accessdate=2014-12-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 2012,  [[K.I.Z.]] and Kraftklub gave an unannounced concert on the roof of the Chemnitz commercial complex ''Terminal 3'' as part of the documentary film series ''Durch die Nacht mit...'' commissioned by [[Arte|ARTE]]. The performance was announced only a few hours before via social networks, despite the ban on dancing on Good Friday, and as a result of the crowds of spectators the police closed off the Chemnitzer Br\u00fcckenstra\u00dfe. <ref>Florian Harlass: [http://www.371stadtmagazin.de/371magazin/items/Kraftklub-Jahresrueckblick-felixkummer-chemnitz-2012-Zuhause-371.html ''Jahresr\u00fcckblick mit K \u2013 Kraftklub 2012'']. 371stadtmagazin.de</ref>\n\nKraftklub refer to their hometown of [[Chemnitz]] as \"Karl-Marx-Stadt\" <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.laut.de/Kraftklub |title=laut.de-Biographie - Kraftklub |website=laut.de |language=de |accessdate=2014-12-01}}</ref> (this was the name the city was known as from 1953 to 1990) - one of their songs on ''Mit K'' is entitled ''Karl-Marx-Stadt'' - and they are known for their trademark poloshirts, varsity jackets and [[suspenders]].<ref name=\"reflect\" />\n\nFor [[Record Store Day]] 2012, Kraftklub released the song ''Songs for Liam'' in a version with [[Casper (rapper)|Casper]] as vinyl single, which is limited to 700 pieces. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/KraftKlub-Feat-Casper-Songs-F%C3%BCr-Liam/release/3555694|title=Kraftklub feat. Casper - Songs f\u00fcr Liam (2012)|last=|first=|date=|website=discogs.com|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIts first concert outside of Germany was at 19 September 2012, in \"La Puerta Grande\" Bar in [[Bogot\u00e1]], thanks to the \"Kolumbien mit K\" tour promoted by the Goethe Institut - Colombia, which took them by Bogot\u00e1, [[Medell\u00edn]] and [[Cali]], each one with two concerts respectively, and one in Cartagena.{{citation needed |date=December 2014}}\n\nIn 2013, Kraftklub was nominated (among others) together with the group [[Frei.Wild]] for the ''music award Echo'' in the category ''Rock/Alternative National''. On 6 Mrach 2013, Kraftklub announced that they want to be removed from the list of nominees, as Kraftklub does not want to be named in the same line as FreiWild. After [[MIA.|Mia.]] and [[Die \u00c4rzte]] also withdrew their participation, Frei.Wild was removed from the list of nominees and Kraftklub received the \"Kritikerpreis National\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ok-magazin.de/entertainment/musik/16855/kraftklub-freuen-sich-nach-nominierten-eklat-ueber-echo-|title=Kraftklub wins 'Echo' after nomination scandel|last=|first=|date=20 March 2013|website=ok-magazin.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe song ''Eure M\u00e4dchen'' can be heard on the soundtrack of the PC and console game [[FIFA 13]]. It is the only German title in the game. Kraftklub has a guest appearance in the song ''Ganz sch\u00f6n okay'' on the album ''Hinterland'' by German rapper Casper.\n\n=== In Schwarz (2014\u20132016) ===\nOn 20 May 2014, the music video ''Hand in Hand'' (in a version with bassist Till Brummer on vocals) of an allegedly new band called ''In Schwarz'' appeared on [[YouTube]]. The video was uploaded by the music label ''[[Audiolith Records]]''. <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6FzA3o9aXrQ</ref> On 2 June 2014, ''In Schwarz'' appeared on the German television show ''Circus HalliGalli'' and revealed themselves as Kraftklub.\n\nOn 20 November 2015, the first live album ''Randale'' was released. Part of the DVD is a recording of the concert in the [[Max-Schmeling-Halle]] in Berlin from 6. March 2015. In January 2016 followed the ''Randale''-tour, in which the band gave concerts in several German cities. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musikexpress.de/kraftklub-hauen-live-dvd-raus-und-gehen-auf-randale-tour-409669/|title=Kraftklub releases new live DVD and goes on tour|last=|first=|date=|website=musikexpress.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Keine Nacht f\u00fcr Niemanden (2017\u2013present) ===\nOn 16 March 2017, the band they released the first single ''Dein Lied'' from the subsequently announced album ''Keine Nacht f\u00fcr Niemand'' during a 10-hour Facebook livestream, which was released on 2 June 2017. The title of the album is an allusion to the album ''Keine Macht f\u00fcr Niemand'' by the band [[Ton Steine Scherben]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.de/kraftklub-album-keine-nacht-fuer-niemand-im-juni-2017-1216323/|title=Kraftklub's new album \"Keine Nacht f\u00fcr Niemand\" to be published in June 2017|last=|first=|date=20 March 2017|website=rollingstone.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n* 2012: ''Mit K''\n* 2014: ''In Schwarz''\n* 2015: ''Randale'' (live album)\n* 2017: ''Keine Nacht f\u00fcr Niemand''\n\n===EPs===\n* 2010: ''Adonis Maximus''\n* 2012: ''Live im Astra Berlin''\n* 2012: ''Songs f\u00fcr Liam''\n\n===Singles===\n* 2011: \"Zu jung\"\n* 2011: \"Ich will nicht nach Berlin\"\n* 2011: \"Eure M\u00e4dchen\"\n* 2012: \"Songs f\u00fcr Liam\"\n* 2012: \"Kein Liebeslied\"\n* 2012: \"Mein Leben\"\n* 2014: \"Hand in Hand\"\n* 2014: \"Unsere Fans\"\n* 2014: \"Wie ich\"\n* 2014: \"Sch\u00fcsse in die Luft\"\n* 2015: \"Blau\"\n* 2015: \"Alles wegen Dir\"\n* 2017: \"Dein Lied\"\n* 2017: \"Fenster\"\n* 2017: \"Sklave\"\n* 2017: \"Chemie Chemie Ya\"\n* 2017: \"Am Ende\"\n* 2018: \"Liebe zu Dritt\"\n\n==Band members==\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:2015 RiP Kraftklub - Felix Brummer by 2eight - 8SC3231.jpg|Felix Brummer (Rap, vocals) in 2015\nFile:2017 RiP - Kraftklub - Karl Schumann - by 2eight - DSC8513.jpg|Karl Schumann (Rhythm guitar, vocals) in 2017\nFile:2015 RiP Kraftklub - Till Brummer by 2eight - 8SC3240.jpg|Till Brummer (Bass) in 2015\nFile:2015 RiP Kraftklub - Steffen Isreal by 2eight - 8SC3355.jpg|Steffen Israel (Lead guitar, keys) in 2015\nFile:2015 RiP Kraftklub - Max Marschk by 2eight - 8SC3298.jpg|Max Marschk (Drums) in 2015\n</gallery>Till and Felix are brothers <ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvtotal.prosieben.de/tvtotal/videos/player/index.html?contentId=122386&initialTab=related|title=Kraftklub mit \"K\" (Event vom 29.09.2011)|language=de|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428173345/http://tvtotal.prosieben.de/tvtotal/videos/player/index.html?contentId=122386&initialTab=related|archivedate=28 April 2012|accessdate=13 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"reflect\" /> and the sons of ''AG. Geige'' member Jan Kummer. Since there is no artistic connection to Kraftklub, the brothers use the surname Brummer instead.\n\n==Song appearances==\n* \"Eure M\u00e4dchen\" from [[EA Sports]]' ''[[FIFA 13]]'' Soundtrack (2012)\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://www.kraftklub.to/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:German rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Participants in the Bundesvision Song Contest]]\n", "name_user": "Lukas3226", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moved files of concerts to the corresponding section within the history chapter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kraftklub"}
{"title_page": "Muhammad Kadhim Khorasani", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[Marja'|Grand Ayatollah]] [[Sheikh]] '''Muhammad-Kadhim Herati Khorasani''' ({{lang-fa|{{nq|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u06a9\u0627\u0638\u0645 \u0647\u0631\u0627\u062a\u0649 \u062e\u0631\u0627\u0633\u0627\u0646\u06cc}}}}; <!--forcibly end r-to-l-->1839 \u2013 12 December 1911), commonly known as '''Akhund Khorasani'''<ref name=\"Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Hairi|first1=A.|last2=Murata|first2=S.|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/akund-molla-mohammad-kazem-korasani|title=A\u1e34\u016aND \u1e34OR\u0100S\u0100N\u012a|date=1984|encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Irannica}}</ref> was an [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[marja']] and philosopher.{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Islam]]|jurisprudence=|parents=Mulla Husayn Herati (father)|background=#ABE9CC|Madh'hab=[[Twelver]] [[Shia Islam]]|location=[[Najaf]], [[Iraq]]|predecessor=[[Mirza Shirazi]]|successor=[[Muhammad Hossein Naini]]|period=1895\u20131911|signature=|website=|influenced=|notable_works=Kefayat al-Usul|notable_ideas=|main_interests=|creed=|denomination=|honorific_prefix=[[Grand Ayatollah]] [[Sheikh]]|occupation=|region=[[Najaf]], [[Iraq]]|nationality=Iranian|other_names=|resting_place=[[Imam Ali Shrine]]|death_place=[[Najaf]], [[Iraq]]|death_date={{death date and age|1911|12|12|1839|}}|birth_place=[[Mashhad]], [[Iran]]|birth_date={{birth year|1839}}|birth_name=|title=|caption=|image=\u0622\u062e\u0648\u0646\u062f \u062e\u0631\u0627\u0633\u0627\u0646\u06cc.jpg|name=Muhammad-Kadhim Khorasani|known_for=''Innovating'' [[Usul al-Fiqh]]|post=[[Grand Ayatollah]]|native_name={{lang|fa|\u0634\u064a\u062e \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0643\u0627\u0638\u0645 \u0647\u0631\u0627\u062a\u0649 \u062e\u0631\u0627\u0633\u0627\u0646\u064a }}}}He is regarded as one of the most important Shia ''[[Mujtahid]]'' at the time.<ref name=\"Meir\" /> He was a lecturer at Najaf seminary for years and significant number of students from \"different regions of the Muslim world\" used to participate his lectures. His most famous work is ''The Sufficiency'' ({{lang-ar|\u06a9\u0641\u0627\u06cc\u0647}}), where he gathered the jurispurdential ideas such as \"continuity\" and \"presented them in a yet more rigorous fashion as a unified theory of jurisprudence\".\n\nHe is known for using his position as a [[Marja'|marja]] for political use in the [[Persian Constitutional Revolution]] (1905\u20131911), where he was one of the main clerical supporters of the revolution. He believed that \"constitutional form of government\" would be the best possible choice in the absence of [[The Twelve Imams|Imam]] and regarded the \"Persian revolution\" a ''[[Jihad]]'' (\"holy war\") in which all Muslims had to participate.\n\nHe died \"suddenly\" and \"mysteriously\", when he aimed to leave Iraq for Iran in order against support constitutionalists' resistance to the [[Anglo-Soviet invasion of Iran|Anglo-Russian invasion in 1911]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nKhorasani was born in [[Mashhad]], where he did his early educations. Then at 20, he left for [[Sabzevar]],<ref name=\"EI3\">{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Amir-Moezzi|first1= Mohammad Ali |authorlink=Mohammad Ali Amir-Moezzi |url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-3/akhund-al-khurasani-COM_23052?s.num=131&s.start=120|title=\u0100kh\u016bnd al- Khur\u0101s\u0101n\u012b|date=2010|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Islam|edition=3rd}}</ref> where he got familiar with [[Islamic philosophy]] under [[Hadi Sabzavari|Molla Hadi Sabzavari]]. He continued Islamic philosophy under Molla Hosayn Kho\u02bei at the Sadr [[seminary]] in [[Tehran]],<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> the city where he learnt [[Logic]] and Hekmat. In 1861 he moved to [[Iraq]] and in [[Najaf]] worked on complementary studies under Grand Ayatollah [[Mirza Shirazi|Mirza Hassan Shirazi]], famous for his campaign against [[Tobacco Protest|the tobacco concession]].<ref name=\"Prophet\"/> Also he studied about two years under [[Morteza Ansari]].<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> Both Morteza Ansari and Mirza Hassan Shirazi were ''[[Marja'|marja-e taqlid]]'' (\"models for emulation\") at the time.<ref name=\"EI3\"/>\n\n==Leader of Shia Muslims==\nShirazi's move [[Samarra]] provided a suitable opportunity for Akhund Khorasani to show his skill in ''[[Fiqh|feqh]]'' and ''osul'' in Najaf while being supported by Shirazi. After Shirazi's death he was recognized as a \"a great religious leader\". Some authors such as [[Ali Davani]] and Shahrestani regard him as the \"sole ''marja-e taqlid'' immediately after Shirazi\". He's also regarded as \"an unquestionable master of [[Principles of Islamic jurisprudence|osul al-feqh]] before [[Mohammad Fazel Sarabiani]]'s death\".<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\nHe was a lecturer at Najaf seminary for years and significant number of students from \"different regions of the Muslim world\" used to participate his lectures.<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> His most famous work is ''The Sufficiency'' ({{lang-ar|\u06a9\u0641\u0627\u06cc\u0647}}), which ranks \"only after Morteza Ansari's treatice on commercial law\" among the legal works written by mullahs in the last two centuries. In ''The Sufficiency'', Khorasani gathered the jurispurdential ideas such as \"continuity\" and \"presented them in a yet more rigorous fashion as a unified theory of jurisprudence\".  Khorasani was not a [[sayyed]] but \"owed his position almost purely to his intellectual accomplishments\".<ref name=\"Prophet\">{{cite book|last1=Mottahedeh|first1=Roy |authorlink=Roy Mottahedeh |title=The Mantle of the Prophet|publisher=Oneworld Publications|isbn=9781780747385|pages=218\u2013219|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YlsQBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Mantle+of+the+Prophet&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjanJjJ7obQAhVISRoKHXL6DJsQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=The%20Mantle%20of%20the%20Prophet&f=false |language=en |accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnder Khorasani's leadership, the [[Usuli]] position became the dominant view.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Acevedo|first1=Gabriel A.|last2=Shah|first2=Sarah|title=Sectarian Affiliation and Gender Traditionalism|journal=Sociology of Islam|date=25 August 2015|volume=3|issue=1-2|pages=1\u201329|doi=10.1163/22131418-00301001|url=http://booksandjournals.brillonline.com/content/journals/10.1163/22131418-00301001|publisher=Brill}}{{subscription required|via=Brill}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nAlthough he warned the scholars for not involving in political activities as he believed that they had other responsibilities, he believed that scholars could act as \"warning voices in society\" and criticize the officials who were not doing their responsibilities correctly. He compared the role of scholars with \"[[salt]] of the earth\" in the sense that they prevent \"decay of power\", should fight against injustice and that they are against \"[[autocratic]] attitudes\".<ref name=\"Religion\">{{cite book|last1=Hustinx|first1=Lesley|last2=Essen|first2=Johan Von|last3=Haers|first3=Jacques|last4=Mels|first4=Sara|title=Religion and Volunteering: Complex, contested and ambiguous relationships|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319045856|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FsokBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA73&dq=akhund+khorasani&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwje3sXWmp3QAhXDBcAKHWbqB-QQ6AEIMDAD#v=onepage&q=akhund%20khorasani&f=false |page=73 |language=en |accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Political activities==\nThe first known Akhund Khorasani's anti-government political activities is related to \"the unrest following the two Russian loans to [[Mozaffar-al-din Shah]]\".<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\nMohammad Kazem Khorasani was also one of the main clerical supporters of the [[Iranian Constitutional Revolution]]<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> and along with [[Mirza Hosayn Tehrani]] and [[Shaikh Abdallah Mazandarani]] he led people against what they called a \"state tyranny\"<ref name=\"Kamali\">{{cite book |last1=Kamali |first1=Mohammad Hashim |authorlink=Mohammad Hashim Kamali |last2=Ramadan |first2=Tariq |author2link=Tariq Ramadan |title=The Middle Path of Moderation in Islam: The Quranic Principle of Wasatiyyah|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190226831 |page=109 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HffzCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA109&lpg=PA109&dq=Mirza+Hosayn+Tehrani&source=bl&ots=PRtXZUkIgK&sig=8Fmq_0kOJidZE2LDy-2Lykx1nrQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjavv2v04rQAhXJShQKHTaTAzUQ6AEIODAJ#v=onepage&q=Mirza%20Hosayn%20Tehrani&f=false |language=en |accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> and issued fatwas and \"sent telegrams to tribal chiefs, prominent national and political leaders, and heads of state in England, France, Germany, and Turkey\". When [[Mohammad Ali Shah]] became king of Iran, Mohammad Kazem Khorasani sent him a \"ten-point\" instruction including points on ptotecting Islam, promoting domestic industries and modern science, stopping foreign powers' intervention in Iran \"while retaining diplomatic relations\", and establishing \"justice and equality\".<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\nHe believed that \"constitutional form of government\" would be the best possible choice in the absence of [[The Twelve Imams|Imam]] and regarded the \"Persian revolution\" a ''[[Jihad]]'' (\"holy war\") in which all Muslims had to participate.<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> When [[Sheikh Fazlollah Noori]] declared journalists non-Muslims for their support of the new Constitutional Assembly, Khorasani retaliated by announcing that Sheikh Fazlollah was himself no longer a Muslim, leading to Fazlollah's execution.<ref name=\"Prophet\"/>{{rp|222}} The reaction to Noori's execution in Najaf harmed Khorasani and other constitution supporters and led to a rivalry with [[Mohammed Kazem Yazdi]].<ref>{{cite book |author=[[Sa\u00efd Amir Arjomand|Said Amir Arjomand]] |title=The Turban for the Crown |year=1989 |publisher=Oxford University Press US\n|isbn=0-19-504258-1 |page=52 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IQci1YIffjYC&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=kazem+yazdi&source=web&ots=yrH7tQXGrg&sig=32ED0rTwHhjLFzoG8lHLCU0HWTk&hl=en\n}}</ref> Khorsani acted more intensively against Mohammad Ali Shah when he shelled the parliament building and executed many \"constitutionalists\".<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\nHe apparently did not have ties with [[Oudh Bequest]] nor he favored British, despite the allegations. He were in an \"equal opposition\" to Russia and Britain, two powers at the time.<ref name=\"EI2\">{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Hairi|first1=Abdul-Hadi|url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-2/khurasani-SIM_4337?s.num=17&s.au=%22Hairi%2C+Abdul+Hadi%22|title=K\u0332h\u0332ur\u0101s\u0101n\u012b|date=|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Islam|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\n==Works and pupils==\nHe authored many books hence titled \"Innovator\" (''al-mujaddid'') of ''Usul al-feqh''. Kifayat al-usul, Khorasani's most important book, is taught in advanced classes at the seminaries as the main text on the methodology of law. It has received \"hundreds of commentaries\".<ref name=\"EI3\"/> The book suppressed ''Qvanin al-Osul'' by Qummi, one of seminary main texts taught at sotuh level.<ref name=\"Meir\">{{cite book|last1=Litvak|first1=Meir |authorlink=Meir Litvak |title=Shi'i Scholars of Nineteenth-Century Iraq: The 'Ulama' of Najaf and Karbala'|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521892964 |page=92 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3pYRFQQG5kEC&pg=PA92&dq=akhund+khorasani&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwje3sXWmp3QAhXDBcAKHWbqB-QQ6AEIKjAC#v=onepage&q=akhund%20khorasani&f=false |language=en |accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref> Also, he wrote one of the most important commentaries on [[Morteza Ansari|Shaykh Morteza al-Ansari]]'s ''Durar al-fawaid fi sharh al-Faraid'', also taught alongside Kifayat al-usul.<ref name=\"EI3\"/>\n\n[[Ayatollah Mirza Hussein Naini]], [[Muhammad Hossein Qaravi|Ayatollah Muhammad Hossein Qaravi]], [[Agha Zia Addin Araghi]] were among his students.<ref name=\"EI3\"/>\n\n==Death==\nHe died \"suddenly\" and \"mysteriously\", when he aimed to leave Iraq for Iran in order against support constitutionalists' resistance to the [[Anglo-Soviet invasion of Iran|Anglo-Russian invasion in 1911]].<ref name=\"EI3\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Iranian Constitutional Revolution]] \n*[[Intellectual movements in Iran]]\n*[[Mirza Malkom Khan]]\n*[[Ayatollah Mirza Hussein Naini|Mirza Hussein Naini]]\n*[[Oudh Bequest]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mohammad-Kazem Khorasani}}\n*{{Official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20130302232751/http://akhondekhorasani.ir/Portal/Home/}} (in Persian))\n\n{{Persian Constitutional Revolution Persions}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khorasani, Mohammad Kazem}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1911 deaths]]\n[[Category:Iranian politicians]]\n[[Category:Iranian writers]]\n[[Category:Iranian Shia clerics]]\n[[Category:People of the Persian Constitutional Revolution]]\n[[Category:Iranian Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:Iranian grand ayatollahs]]\n[[Category:Shia Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:Burials at Imam Ali Mosque]]\n", "text_old": "[[Marja'|Grand Ayatollah]] [[Sheikh]] '''Muhammad-Kadhim Herati Khorasani''' ({{lang-fa|{{nq|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u06a9\u0627\u0638\u0645 \u0647\u0631\u0627\u062a\u0649 \u062e\u0631\u0627\u0633\u0627\u0646\u06cc}}}}; 1839\u2013December 12, 1911), commonly known as '''Akhund Khorasani'''<ref name=\"Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Hairi|first1=A.|last2=Murata|first2=S.|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/akund-molla-mohammad-kazem-korasani|title=A\u1e34\u016aND \u1e34OR\u0100S\u0100N\u012a|date=1984|encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Irannica}}</ref> was an [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[marja']] and philosopher.{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Islam]]|jurisprudence=|parents=Mulla Husayn Herati (father)|background=#ABE9CC|Madh'hab=[[Twelver]] [[Shia Islam]]|location=[[Najaf]], [[Iraq]]|predecessor=[[Mirza Shirazi]]|successor=[[Muhammad Hossein Naini]]|period=1895\u20131911|signature=|website=|influenced=|notable_works=Kefayat al-Usul|notable_ideas=|main_interests=|creed=|denomination=|honorific_prefix=[[Grand Ayatollah]] [[Sheikh]]|occupation=|region=[[Najaf]], [[Iraq]]|nationality=Iranian|other_names=|resting_place=[[Imam Ali Shrine]]|death_place=[[Najaf]], [[Iraq]]|death_date={{death date and age|1911|12|12|1839|}}|birth_place=[[Mashhad]], [[Iran]]|birth_date={{birth year|1839}}|birth_name=|title=|caption=|image=\u0622\u062e\u0648\u0646\u062f \u062e\u0631\u0627\u0633\u0627\u0646\u06cc.jpg|name=Muhammad-Kadhim Khorasani|known_for=''Innovating'' [[Usul al-Fiqh]]|post=[[Grand Ayatollah]]|native_name={{lang|fa|\u0634\u064a\u062e \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0643\u0627\u0638\u0645 \u0647\u0631\u0627\u062a\u0649 \u062e\u0631\u0627\u0633\u0627\u0646\u064a }}}}He's regarded as one of the most important Shia ''[[Mujtahid]]'' at the time.<ref name=\"Meir\" /> He was a lecturer at Najaf seminary for years and significant number of students from \"different regions of the Muslim world\" used to participate his lectures. His most famous work is ''The Sufficiency'' ({{lang-ar|\u06a9\u0641\u0627\u06cc\u0647}}) where he gathered the jurispurdential ideas such as `continuity` and \"presented them in a yet more rigorous fashion as a unified theory of jurisprudence.\"\n\nHe is known for using his position as a [[Marja'|marja]] for political use in the [[Persian Constitutional Revolution]] (1905-1911) where he was one of the main clerical supporters of the revolution. He believed that \"constitutional form of government\" would be the best possible choice in the absence of [[The Twelve Imams|Imam]] and regarded the \"Persian revolution\" a ''[[Jihad]]'' (\"holy war\") in which all Muslims had to participate.\n\nHe died \"suddenly\" and \"mysteriously\", when he aimed to leave Iraq for Iran in order against support constitutionalists' resistance to the [[Anglo-Soviet invasion of Iran|Anglo-Russian invasion in 1911]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nKhorasani was born in [[Mashhad]] where he did his early educations. Then he left for [[Sabzevar]] at 20<ref name=\"EI3\">{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Amir-Moezzi|first1= Mohammad Ali|url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-3/akhund-al-khurasani-COM_23052?s.num=131&s.start=120|title=\u0100kh\u016bnd al- Khur\u0101s\u0101n\u012b|date=2010|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Islam|edition=3rd}}</ref> where he got familiar with [[Islamic philosophy]] under [[Hadi Sabzavari|Molla Hadi Sabzavari]]. He continued Islamic philosophy under Molla Hosayn Kho\u02bei at the Sadr [[seminary]] in [[Tehran]],<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> the city where he learnt [[Logic]] and Hekmat. In 1861 he moved to [[Iraq]] and in [[Najaf]] worked on complementary studies under Grand Ayatollah [[Mirza Shirazi|Mirza Hassan Shirazi]], famous for his campaign against [[Tobacco Protest|the tobacco concession]].<ref name=\"Prophet\"/> Also he studied about two years under [[Morteza Ansari]].<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> Both Morteza Ansari and Mirza Hassan Shirazi were ''[[Marja'|marja-e taqlid]]'' (\"models for emulation\") at the time.<ref name=\"EI3\"/>\n\n==Leader of Shia Muslims==\nShirazi's move [[Samarra]] provided a suitable opportunity for Akhund Khorasani to show his skill in ''[[Fiqh|feqh]]'' and ''osul'' in Najaf while being supported by Shirazi. After Shirazi's death he was recognized as a \"a great religious leader.\" Some authors such as [[Ali Davani]] and Shahrestani regard him as the \"sole ''marja-e taqlid'' immediately after Shirazi.\" He's also regarded as \"an unquestionable master of [[Principles of Islamic jurisprudence|osul al-feqh]] before [[Mohammad Fazel Sarabiani]]\u2019s death.\"<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\nHe was a lecturer at Najaf seminary for years and significant number of students from \"different regions of the Muslim world\" used to participate his lectures.<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> His most famous work is ''The Sufficiency'' ({{lang-ar|\u06a9\u0641\u0627\u06cc\u0647}}) which ranks \"only after Morteza Ansari's treatice on commercial law\" among the legal works written by mullahs in the last two centuries. In ''The Sufficiency'', Khorasani gathered the jurispurdential ideas such as `continuity` and \"presented them in a yet more rigorous fashion as a unified theory of jurisprudence.\"  Khorasani was not a [[sayyed]] but \"owed his position almost purely to his intellectual accomplishments.\"<ref name=\"Prophet\">{{cite book|last1=Mottahedeh|first1=Roy|title=The Mantle of the Prophet|publisher=Oneworld Publications|isbn=9781780747385|pages=218\u2013219|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YlsQBwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Mantle+of+the+Prophet&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjanJjJ7obQAhVISRoKHXL6DJsQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=The%20Mantle%20of%20the%20Prophet&f=false|accessdate=1 November 2016|language=en}}</ref>\n\nUnder Khorasani's leadership, the [[Usuli]] position became the dominant view.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Acevedo|first1=Gabriel A.|last2=Shah|first2=Sarah|title=Sectarian Affiliation and Gender Traditionalism|journal=Sociology of Islam|date=25 August 2015|volume=3|issue=1-2|pages=1\u201329|doi=10.1163/22131418-00301001|url=http://booksandjournals.brillonline.com/content/journals/10.1163/22131418-00301001|publisher=Brill}}{{subscription required|via=Brill}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nAlthough he warned the scholars for not involving in political activities as he believed that they had other responsibilities, he believed that scholars could act as \"warning voices in society\" and criticize the officials who were not doing their responsibilities correctly. He compared the role of scholars with \"[[salt]] of the earth\" in the sense that they prevent \"decay of power\", should fight against injustice and that they are against \"[[autocratic]] attitudes\"<ref name=\"Religion\">{{cite book|last1=Hustinx|first1=Lesley|last2=Essen|first2=Johan Von|last3=Haers|first3=Jacques|last4=Mels|first4=Sara|title=Religion and Volunteering: Complex, contested and ambiguous relationships|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319045856|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FsokBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA73&dq=akhund+khorasani&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwje3sXWmp3QAhXDBcAKHWbqB-QQ6AEIMDAD#v=onepage&q=akhund%20khorasani&f=false|accessdate=10 November 2016|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Political activities==\nThe first known Akhund Khorasani's anti-government political activities is related to \"the unrest following the two Russian loans to [[Mozaffar-al-din Shah]].\"<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\nMohammad Kazem Khorasani was also one of the main clerical supporters of the [[Iranian Constitutional Revolution]]<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> and along with [[Mirza Hosayn Tehrani]] and [[Shaikh Abdallah Mazandarani]] he led people against what they called a \"state tyranny\"<ref name=\"Kamali\">{{cite book|last1=Kamali|first1=Mohammad Hashim|last2=Ramadan|first2=Tariq|title=The Middle Path of Moderation in Islam: The Quranic Principle of Wasatiyyah|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190226831|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HffzCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA109&lpg=PA109&dq=Mirza+Hosayn+Tehrani&source=bl&ots=PRtXZUkIgK&sig=8Fmq_0kOJidZE2LDy-2Lykx1nrQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjavv2v04rQAhXJShQKHTaTAzUQ6AEIODAJ#v=onepage&q=Mirza%20Hosayn%20Tehrani&f=false|accessdate=2 November 2016|language=en}}</ref> and issued fatwas and \"sent telegrams to tribal chiefs, prominent national and political leaders, and heads of state in England, France, Germany, and Turkey.\" When [[Mohammad Ali Shah]] became king of Iran, Mohammad Kazem Khorasani sent him a \"ten-point\" instruction including points on ptotecting Islam, promoting domestic industries and modern science, stopping foreign powers' intervention in Iran \"while retaining diplomatic relations\", and establishing \"justice and equality\".<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\nHe believed that \"constitutional form of government\" would be the best possible choice in the absence of [[The Twelve Imams|Imam]] and regarded the \"Persian revolution\" a ''[[Jihad]]'' (\"holy war\") in which all Muslims had to participate.<ref name=\"Iranica\"/> When [[Sheikh Fazlollah Noori]] declared journalists non-Muslims for their support of the new Constitutional Assembly, Khorasani retaliated by announcing that Sheikh Fazlollah was himself no longer a Muslim, leading to Fazlollah's execution.<ref name=\"Prophet\"/>{{rp|222}} The reaction to Noori's execution in Najaf harmed Khorasani and other constitution supporters and led to a rivalry with [[Mohammed Kazem Yazdi]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Turban for the Crown|author=Said Amir Arjomand|year=1989|publisher=Oxford University Press US\n|isbn=0-19-504258-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IQci1YIffjYC&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=kazem+yazdi&source=web&ots=yrH7tQXGrg&sig=32ED0rTwHhjLFzoG8lHLCU0HWTk&hl=en\n}}</ref> Khorsani acted more intensively against Mohammad Ali Shah when he shelled the parliament building and executed many \"constitutionalists\".<ref name=\"Iranica\"/>\n\nHe apparently did not have ties with [[Oudh Bequest]] nor he favored British, despite the allegations. He were in an \"equal opposition\" to Russia and Britain, two powers at the time.<ref name=\"EI2\">{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Hairi|first1=Abdul-Hadi|url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-2/khurasani-SIM_4337?s.num=17&s.au=%22Hairi%2C+Abdul+Hadi%22|title=K\u0332h\u0332ur\u0101s\u0101n\u012b|date=|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Islam|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\n==Works and pupils==\nHe authored many books hence titled \"Innovator\" (''al-mujaddid'') of ''Usul al-feqh''. Kifayat al-usul, Khorasani's most important book, is taught in advanced classes at the seminaries as the main text on the methodology of law. It has received \"hundreds of commentaries\".<ref name=\"EI3\"/> The book suppressed ''Qvanin al-Osul'' by Qummi, one of seminary main texts taught at sotuh level.<ref name=\"Meir\">{{cite book|last1=Litvak|first1=Meir|title=Shi'i Scholars of Nineteenth-Century Iraq: The 'Ulama' of Najaf and Karbala'|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521892964|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3pYRFQQG5kEC&pg=PA92&dq=akhund+khorasani&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwje3sXWmp3QAhXDBcAKHWbqB-QQ6AEIKjAC#v=onepage&q=akhund%20khorasani&f=false|accessdate=10 November 2016|language=en}}</ref> Also, he wrote one of the most important commentaries on [[Morteza Ansari|Shaykh Morteza al-Ansari]]'s ''Durar al-fawaid fi sharh al-Faraid'', also taught alongside Kifayat al-usul.<ref name=\"EI3\"/>\n\n[[Ayatollah Mirza Hussein Naini]], [[Muhammad Hossein Qaravi|Ayatollah Muhammad Hossein Qaravi]], [[Agha Zia Addin Araghi]] were among his students.<ref name=\"EI3\"/>\n\n==Death==\nHe died \"suddenly\" and \"mysteriously\", when he aimed to leave Iraq for Iran in order against support constitutionalists' resistance to the [[Anglo-Soviet invasion of Iran|Anglo-Russian invasion in 1911]].<ref name=\"EI3\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Iranian Constitutional Revolution]] \n*[[Intellectual movements in Iran]]\n*[[Mirza Malkom Khan]]\n*[[Ayatollah Mirza Hussein Naini|Mirza Hussein Naini]]\n*[[Oudh Bequest]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mohammad-Kazem Khorasani}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130302232751/http://akhondekhorasani.ir/Portal/Home/ Official website]\n\n{{Persian Constitutional Revolution Persions}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khorasani, Mohammad Kazem}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1911 deaths]]\n[[Category:Iranian politicians]]\n[[Category:Iranian writers]]\n[[Category:Iranian Shia clerics]]\n[[Category:People of the Persian Constitutional Revolution]]\n[[Category:Iranian Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:Iranian grand ayatollahs]]\n[[Category:Shia Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:Burials at Imam Ali Mosque]]\n", "name_user": "Anomalocaris", "label": "safe", "comment": "comma before nonrestrictive clause; logical quotes; 