{"title_page": "John Hodge (English footballer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = John Hodge\n| image = \n| fullname = \n| height = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|4|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Ormskirk]], England\n| position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1990\u20131991 \n| years2 = 1991\u20131993 \n| years3 = 1993\u20131996 \n| years4 = 1996\u20131998 \n| years5 = 1998\u20132000 \n| years6 = 2000 \n| years7 = 2000\u20132003 \n| years8 = 2003\n| clubs1 = [[Falmouth Town A.F.C.|Falmouth Town]] \n| clubs2 = [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] \n| clubs3 = [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] \n| clubs4 = [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] \n| clubs5 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] \n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] (loan) \n| clubs7 = [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] \n| clubs8 = [[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]]\n| caps1 = ?   \n| caps2 = 65  \n| caps3 = 102  \n| caps4 = 76  \n| caps5 = 52   \n| caps6 = 1   \n| caps7 = 59   \n| caps8 = 0   \n| goals1 = ?  \n| goals2 = 10  \n| goals3 = 10  \n| goals4 = 12  \n| goals5 = 1  \n| goals6 = 0  \n| goals7 = 2  \n| goals8 = 0\n}}\n'''John Hodge''' (born 1 April 1969) is a right winger who earned cult status at Gillingham. He was regarded as a supersub, coming on late in games to create chances and take on tiring opposition left-backs.\n\nHe went on trial with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] from November 1989 to December 1989. Whilst at Swansea he was a part of the team that won after a [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] in the [[1994 Football League Trophy Final]].<ref name=\"FLT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-sublime-swansea-glide-to-victory-welsh-pride-stirred-at-wembley-1372474.html|title=Football: Sublime Swansea glide to victory: Welsh pride stirred at Wembley|newspaper=The Independent|date=25 April 1994|accessdate=12 June 2019|author=White, Clive}}</ref> He joined [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] in July 1998.<ref name=\"PFA\">{{cite book\n | last = Hugman\n | first = Barry J.\n | title = The PFA Premier & Football League Players' Records 1946-2005\n | publisher = Queen Anne Press\n | year = 2005\n | pages = 292\n | isbn = 1-85291-665-6 }}</ref> \n\nHis only league goal was a second-half injury-time equaliser against Macclesfield on 3 October 1998. He was regarded as a 'supersub', coming off the substitute's bench to often devastating effect - including setting up Robert Taylor for a last-minute goal against Fulham on 28 November 1998, and Andy Thomson for a 100th-minute winner against Walsall in a FA Cup replay on 8 January 2000.\n\nHe was the only Gillingham player to successfully convert a penalty in their 3-1 penalty shoot-out defeat to Manchester City in the 1998/99 Division Two Play-off final. Hodge was signed by [[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]] in January 2003.<ref name=\"Britton signs Hodge\">{{cite news\n| title = Britton signs Hodge\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/k/kidderminster_harriers/2635761.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 2003-01-07\n| accessdate = 2007-09-04}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|bg    = gold\n|fg    = navy\n|title = Awards\n|list1 =\n{{1997\u201398 Football League Second Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Swansea City A.F.C. Player of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hodge, John}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ormskirk]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Falmouth Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Exeter City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swansea City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Walsall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gillingham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Northampton Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kidderminster Harriers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n\n\n{{England-footy-midfielder-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = John Hodge\n| image = \n| fullname = \n| height = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|4|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Ormskirk]], England\n| position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1990\u20131991 \n| years2 = 1991\u20131993 \n| years3 = 1993\u20131996 \n| years4 = 1996\u20131998 \n| years5 = 1998\u20132000 \n| years6 = 2000 \n| years7 = 2000\u20132003 \n| years8 = 2003\n| clubs1 = [[Falmouth Town A.F.C.|Falmouth Town]] \n| clubs2 = [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] \n| clubs3 = [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] \n| clubs4 = [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] \n| clubs5 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] \n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] (loan) \n| clubs7 = [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] \n| clubs8 = [[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]]\n| caps1 = ?   \n| caps2 = 65  \n| caps3 = 102  \n| caps4 = 76  \n| caps5 = 52   \n| caps6 = 1   \n| caps7 = 59   \n| caps8 = 0   \n| goals1 = ?  \n| goals2 = 10  \n| goals3 = 10  \n| goals4 = 12  \n| goals5 = 1  \n| goals6 = 0  \n| goals7 = 2  \n| goals8 = 0\n}}\n'''John Hodge''' (born 1 April 1969) is a right winger who earned cult status at Gillingham. He was regarded as a supersub, coming on late in games to create chances and take on tiring opposition left-backs.\n\nHe went on trial with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] from November 1989 to December 1989. Whilst at Swansea he was a part of the team that won after a [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] in the [[1994 Football League Trophy Final]].<ref name=\"FLT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-sublime-swansea-glide-to-victory-welsh-pride-stirred-at-wembley-1372474.html|title=Football: Sublime Swansea glide to victory: Welsh pride stirred at Wembley|newspaper=The Independent|date=25 April 1994|accessdate=12 June 2019|author=White, Clive}}</ref> He joined [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] in July 1998.<ref name=\"PFA\">{{cite book\n | last = Hugman\n | first = Barry J.\n | title = The PFA Premier & Football League Players' Records 1946-2005\n | publisher = Queen Anne Press\n | year = 2005\n | pages = 292\n | isbn = 1-85291-665-6 }}</ref> His only league goal was a second-half injury-time equaliser against Macclesfield on 3 October 1998. He was regarded as a 'supersub', coming off the substitute's bench to often devastating effect - including setting up Robert Taylor for a last-minute goal against Fulham on 28 November 1998, and Andy Thomson for a 100th-minute winner against Walsall in a FA Cup replay on 8 January 2000.\n\nHe was the only Gillingham player to successfully convert a penalty in their 3-1 penalty shoot-out defeat to Manchester City in the 1998/99 Division Two Play-off final. Hodge was signed by [[Kidderminster Harriers F.C.|Kidderminster Harriers]] in January 2003.<ref name=\"Britton signs Hodge\">{{cite news\n| title = Britton signs Hodge\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/k/kidderminster_harriers/2635761.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| date = 2003-01-07\n| accessdate = 2007-09-04}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|bg    = gold\n|fg    = navy\n|title = Awards\n|list1 =\n{{1997\u201398 Football League Second Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Swansea City A.F.C. Player of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hodge, John}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ormskirk]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Falmouth Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Exeter City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swansea City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Walsall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gillingham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Northampton Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kidderminster Harriers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n\n\n{{England-footy-midfielder-1960s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Infogapp1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Hodge_(English_footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Cryovolcano", "text_new": "{{short description|A type of volcano that erupts volatiles such as water, ammonia or methane, instead of molten rock}}\n{{for|the related terrestrial formation|Ice volcano}}\n{{expert needed|Volcanoes|ex2=Solar System|date=February 2008}}\n[[Image:Doom Mons, Sotra Patera, Mohini Fluctus (cropped).png|thumb|right|[[Doom Mons]], one of the most reliably identified cryovolcanoes on [[Saturn]]'s moon [[Titan (moon)|Titan]]<ref name=Lopes_2013/>]]\nA '''cryovolcano''' (sometimes informally called an '''ice volcano''') is a type of [[volcano]] that erupts [[volatiles]] such as [[water]], [[ammonia]] or [[methane]], instead of [[lava|molten rock]].<ref name=\"IES-Cryovolcanism\">{{cite web |url=http://www.daviddarling.info/encyclopedia/C/cryovolcanism.html |title=Cryovolcanism |publisher=[[Internet Encyclopedia of Science]] |editor=Darling, David}}</ref> Collectively referred to as '''cryomagma''', '''cryolava''' or ice-volcanic melt,<ref name=\"IES-Cryovolcanism\" /> these substances are usually [[liquid]]s and can form [[plume (hydrodynamics)|plumes]], but can also be in [[vapor|vapour]] form. After eruption, cryomagma is expected to condense to a [[solid]] form when exposed to the very low surrounding [[temperature]]. Cryovolcanoes may potentially form on [[icy moon]]s and other objects with abundant water past the Solar System's [[Frost line (astrophysics)|snow line]] (such as [[Pluto]]<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.nature.com/news/icy-volcanoes-may-dot-pluto-s-surface-1.18756 |title=Ice volcanoes may dot Pluto's surface |journal=Nature |author=Witze, Alexandra|doi=10.1038/nature.2015.18756 |year=2015 }}</ref>). A number of features have been identified as possible cryovolcanoes on Pluto, [[Titan (moon)|Titan]] and [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]]. In addition, although they are not known to form volcanoes, ice geysers have been observed on [[Enceladus]] and potentially [[Triton (moon)|Triton]].\n\nOne potential energy source on some solar system bodies for melting ices and producing cryovolcanoes is [[tidal acceleration|tidal friction]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Greenberg|first=Richard|date=2002|title=Tidal-tectonic processes and their implications for the character of Europa's icy crust|journal=Reviews of Geophysics|language=en|volume=40|issue=2|doi=10.1029/2000rg000096|issn=8755-1209}}</ref> Translucent deposits of frozen materials create a subsurface [[greenhouse effect]] that would accumulate the required [[heat]].\n\nSigns of past warming of the Kuiper belt object [[50000 Quaoar|Quaoar]]<ref name=\"Jewitt2004\">{{cite journal | author=Jewitt, D.C. |author2=J. Luu | title=Crystalline water ice on the Kuiper belt object (50000) Quaoar | journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] | volume=432 | issue=7018 | year=2004 | pages=731\u20133 | doi=10.1038/nature03111 | pmid = 15592406 |bibcode = 2004Natur.432..731J |author-link=David Jewitt }}. [http://www2.ess.ucla.edu/~jewitt/papers/2004/JL2004.pdf Reprint] on Jewitt's site (pdf)</ref> have led scientists to speculate that it exhibited cryovolcanism in the past. [[Radioactive decay]] could provide the energy necessary for such activity, as cryovolcanoes can emit water mixed with ammonia, which would melt at {{convert|\u221295|\u00b0C|K|order=flip|sigfig=2}} and create an extremely cold liquid that would flow out of the volcano.\n\n==Observations==\n[[Image:Fountains of Enceladus PIA07758.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Plumes of [[Enceladus]], feeding [[Saturn]]'s [[Rings of Saturn|E Ring]], seem to arise from the \"[[Tiger Stripes (Enceladus)|Tiger Stripes]]\" near the south pole.]]\n\nOn November 27, 2005, ''[[Cassini\u2013Huygens|Cassini]]'' photographed [[geyser]]s on the south [[Geographical pole|pole]] of [[Enceladus (moon)|Enceladus]].<ref name=\"NYT-20150315\">{{cite news |last=Chang |first=Kenneth \n|title=Suddenly, It Seems, Water Is Everywhere in Solar System\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/13/science/space/suddenly-it-seems-water-is-everywhere-in-solar-system.html |date=March 12, 2015 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 12, 2015 }}</ref> (See also: [[Enceladus#South polar plumes|Enceladus (cryovolcanism)]].)\n\nIndirect evidence of cryovolcanic activity was later observed on several other [[icy moon]]s of the [[Solar System]], including [[Europa (moon)|Europa]], [[Titan (moon)|Titan]], [[Ganymede (moon)|Ganymede]], and [[Miranda (moon)|Miranda]]. ''Cassini'' has observed several features thought to be cryovolcanoes on Titan, notably [[Doom Mons]] with adjacent [[Sotra Patera]], a feature regarded as \"the very best evidence, by far, for volcanic topography anywhere documented on an icy satellite.\"<ref name=\"NASA statement\">\"[http://saturn.jpl.nasa.gov/news/newsreleases/newsrelease20101214/ Cassini Spots Potential Ice Volcano on Saturn Moon]\". NASA, December 14, 2010</ref> Cryovolcanism is one process hypothesized to be a significant source of the methane found in Titan's atmosphere.<ref name=\"rain\">{{cite web |title=Cassini Finds Hydrocarbon Rains May Fill The Lakes |author=Media Relations Office: Cassini Imaging Central Laboratory For Operations |publisher=Space Science Institute, Boulder, Colorado |date=2009 |url=http://ciclops.org/view.php?id=5471&js=1 |accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, observations by the [[Gemini Observatory]] showing patches of ammonia hydrates and water crystals on the surface of [[Pluto]]'s moon [[Charon (moon)|Charon]] suggested the presence of active cryovolcanoes or cryogeysers.<ref name=ice>{{cite web|title=Charon: An ice machine in the ultimate deep freeze|work=Gemini Observatory|year=2007|url=http://www.spaceflightnow.com/news/n0707/17charon/|accessdate=18 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.iop.org/EJ/article/0004-637X/663/2/1406/70488.html | author=Cook | title=Near-Infrared Spectroscopy of Charon: Possible Evidence for Cryovolcanism on Kuiper Belt Objects | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | volume=663 | issue=2 | pages=1406\u20131419 | year=2007 | doi=10.1086/518222 | last2=Desch | first2=Steven J. | last3=Roush | first3=Ted L. | last4=Trujillo | first4=Chadwick A. | last5=Geballe | first5=T. R. | bibcode=2007ApJ...663.1406C|display-authors=etal| doi-access=free }}</ref> Subsequent observations by New Horizons in 2015 found that Charon has a youthful surface, supporting this idea.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beatty |first=Kelly |url=http://www.skyandtelescope.com/astronomy-news/charon-cracked-cratered-and-crazy-100220155/ |title=Charon: Cracked, Cratered, and Colorful |work=Sky and Telescope |date=2 October 2015 |accessdate=2015-10-03 }}</ref> Pluto itself has two features that have been identified as possible cryovolcanoes, being mountains with indented peaks.<ref name = \"Witze2015-11-09\">{{cite journal\n | url = http://www.nature.com/news/icy-volcanoes-may-dot-pluto-s-surface-1.18756\n | title = Icy volcanoes may dot Pluto's surface\n | last = Witze | first = A. | date = 2015-11-09 | journal = Nature News\n | doi=10.1038/nature.2015.18756 | access-date = 2015-11-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, two distinct bright spots inside a crater of the [[dwarf planet]] [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] were imaged by the ''[[Dawn (spacecraft)|Dawn]]'' spacecraft, leading to speculation about a possible cryovolcanic origin.<ref name = \"O'Neill2015.02.25\">{{cite web\n | last = O'Neill | first = I. | title = Ceres' Mystery Bright Dots May Have Volcanic Origin\n | publisher = [[Discovery Communications]]\n | date = 25 February 2015 | accessdate = 1 March 2015\n | url = http://news.discovery.com/space/ceres-mystery-bright-dots-may-have-volcanic-origin-150225.htm\n }}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\nIn September 2016, NASA JPL and NASA Goddard scientists released findings that large [[Ahuna Dome]] on Ceres is a \"volcanic dome unlike any seen elsewhere in the solar system. [The large] mountain is likely volcanic in nature. Specifically, it would be a cryovolcano -- a volcano that erupts a liquid made of volatiles such as water, instead of silicates. ... the only known example of a cryovolcano that potentially formed from a salty mud mix, and that formed in the geologically recent past.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://dawn.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news-detail.html?id=6611 | title=News}}</ref> In addition, at least some of Ceres' well known bright spots (notably including the ones in Occator crater) are likely also cryovolcanic in origin.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Ceres_The_tiny_world_where_volcanoes_erupt_ice_999.html | title=Ceres: The tiny world where volcanoes erupt ice}}</ref> A study published in March 2017 suggests that Occator's most recent large eruption occurred about 4 million years ago and thus that Ceres may still be active.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/space/solar-system/a25552/ice-volcanoes-ceres-active/ | title=The Ice Volcanoes of Ceres Were Highly Active a Few Million Years Ago| date=2017-03-06}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery |align=center\n| title  = Cryovolcanism on [[Enceladus]]\n| lines  = 2\n| width  = 250\n| height = 250\n|File:Enceladus Cold Geyser Model.svg|One possible scheme for Enceladus's cryovolcanism\n|File:PIA19059-SaturnMoon-Enceladus-OceanMethane-20150311.png|Possible origins of methane found in plumes through its subsurface ocean\n|File:Enceladus plume molecules.jpg|Chemical composition of the plumes of Enceladus\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{annotated link|List of extraterrestrial volcanoes}}\n*{{annotated link|Ice volcano}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=Lopes_2013>{{cite journal\n |author1=Lopes, R. M. C. |author2=Kirk, R. L. |author3=Mitchell, K. L. |title  = Cryovolcanism on Titan: New results from Cassini RADAR and VIMS\n |journal= Journal of Geophysical Research: Planets\n |year   = 2013\n |number = 3\n |volume = 118\n |pages  = 416\u2013435\n |doi    = 10.1002/jgre.20062\n |bibcode= 2013JGRE..118..416L\n |display-authors=etal|url= https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-00807740/file/Lopes_et_al-2013-Journal_of_Geophysical_Research__Planets.pdf\n }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nineplanets.org/triton.html Triton] - Triton at the eight Planets\n* [http://www.solarviews.com/cap/nep/triton1.htm South Pole of Triton] - Triton at SolarViews.com\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060818152154/http://www.planetary.org/news/2005/0730_Enceladus_South_Polar_Stripes_Spew.html Enceladus' South Polar Stripes Spew \"Warm\" Water] - News article at the [http://www.planetary.org Planetary Society]\n* [http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/lpsc2007/pdf/1901.pdf Cryovolcanism on Charon and other Kuiper Belt Objects]\n* [http://www.geo.mtu.edu/volcanoes/ice/ Ice Volcanoes of Lake Superior's South Shore]\n* {{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/yblog_thelookout/20110208/ts_yblog_thelookout/ice-volcanoes-are-all-the-rage-this-winter |title=Ice volcanoes are all the rage this winter: How do you stimulate a regional tourist economy? |work=The Lookout |publisher=[[Yahoo News]]\n|first1=Brett Michael |last1=Dykes |date=February 8, 2011 |accessdate=February 8, 2011}}\n* {{cite news |url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/milwaukee/115448834.html |title=Ice volcanoes attract curious explorers to Lake Michigan shore: Experts warn to explore formations with caution |first1=Karen |last1=Herzog |publisher=[[Journal Sentinel]] |date=February 6, 2011 |accessdate=February 8, 2011}}\n\n{{Volcanoes}}\n\n[[Category:Volcanology]]\n[[Category:Planetary geology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A type of volcano that erupts volatiles such as water, ammonia or methane, instead of molten rock}}\n{{for|the related terrestrial formation|Ice volcano}}\n{{expert needed|Volcanoes|ex2=Solar System|date=February 2008}}\n[[Image:Doom Mons, Sotra Patera, Mohini Fluctus (cropped).png|thumb|right|[[Doom Mons]], one of the most reliably identified cryovolcanoes on [[Saturn]]'s moon [[Titan (moon)|Titan]]<ref name=Lopes_2013/>]]\nA '''cryovolcano''' (sometimes informally called an '''ice volcano''') is a type of [[volcano]] that erupts [[volatiles]] such as [[water]], [[ammonia]] or [[methane]], instead of [[lava|molten rock]].<ref name=\"IES-Cryovolcanism\">{{cite web |url=http://www.daviddarling.info/encyclopedia/C/cryovolcanism.html |title=Cryovolcanism |publisher=[[Internet Encyclopedia of Science]] |editor=Darling, David}}</ref> Collectively referred to as '''cryomagma''', '''cryolava''' or ice-volcanic melt,<ref name=\"IES-Cryovolcanism\" /> these substances are usually [[liquid]]s and can form [[plume (hydrodynamics)|plumes]], but can also be in [[vapor|vapour]] form. After eruption, cryomagma is expected to condense to a [[solid]] form when exposed to the very low surrounding [[temperature]]. Cryovolcanoes may potentially form on [[icy moon]]s and other objects with abundant water past the Solar System's [[Frost line (astrophysics)|snow line]] (such as [[Pluto]]<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.nature.com/news/icy-volcanoes-may-dot-pluto-s-surface-1.18756 |title=Ice volcanoes may dot Pluto's surface |journal=Nature |author=Witze, Alexandra|doi=10.1038/nature.2015.18756 |year=2015 }}</ref>). A number of features have been identified as possible cryovolcanoes on Pluto, [[Titan (moon)|Titan]] and [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]]. In addition, although they are not known to form volcanoes, ice geysers have been observed on [[Enceladus]] and potentially [[Triton (moon)|Triton]].\n\nOne potential energy source on some solar system bodies for melting ices and producing cryovolcanoes is [[tidal acceleration|tidal friction]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Greenberg|first=Richard|date=2002|title=Tidal-tectonic processes and their implications for the character of Europa's icy crust|journal=Reviews of Geophysics|language=en|volume=40|issue=2|doi=10.1029/2000rg000096|issn=8755-1209}}</ref> Translucent deposits of frozen materials create a subsurface [[greenhouse effect]] that would accumulate the required [[heat]].\n\nSigns of past warming of the Kuiper belt object [[50000 Quaoar|Quaoar]]<ref name=\"Jewitt2004\">{{cite journal | author=Jewitt, D.C. |author2=J. Luu | title=Crystalline water ice on the Kuiper belt object (50000) Quaoar | journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] | volume=432 | issue=7018 | year=2004 | pages=731\u20133 | doi=10.1038/nature03111 | pmid = 15592406 |bibcode = 2004Natur.432..731J |author-link=David Jewitt }}. [http://www2.ess.ucla.edu/~jewitt/papers/2004/JL2004.pdf Reprint] on Jewitt's site (pdf)</ref> have led scientists to speculate that it exhibited cryovolcanism in the past. [[Radioactive decay]] could provide the energy necessary for such activity, as cryovolcanoes can emit water mixed with ammonia, which would melt at {{convert|\u221295|\u00b0C|K|order=flip|sigfig=2}} and create an extremely cold liquid that would flow out of the volcano.\n\n==Observations==\n[[Image:Fountains of Enceladus PIA07758.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Plumes of [[Enceladus]], feeding [[Saturn]]'s [[Rings of Saturn|E Ring]], seem to arise from the \"[[Tiger Stripes (Enceladus)|Tiger Stripes]]\" near the south pole.]]\n\nOn November 27, 2005, ''[[Cassini\u2013Huygens|Cassini]]'' photographed [[geyser]]s on the south [[Geographical pole|pole]] of [[Enceladus (moon)|Enceladus]].<ref name=\"NYT-20150315\">{{cite news |last=Chang |first=Kenneth \n|title=Suddenly, It Seems, Water Is Everywhere in Solar System\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/13/science/space/suddenly-it-seems-water-is-everywhere-in-solar-system.html |date=March 12, 2015 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 12, 2015 }}</ref> (See also: [[Enceladus#Cryovolcanism|Enceladus (Cryovolcanism)]].)\n\nIndirect evidence of cryovolcanic activity was later observed on several other [[icy moon]]s of the [[Solar System]], including [[Europa (moon)|Europa]], [[Titan (moon)|Titan]], [[Ganymede (moon)|Ganymede]], and [[Miranda (moon)|Miranda]]. ''Cassini'' has observed several features thought to be cryovolcanoes on Titan, notably [[Doom Mons]] with adjacent [[Sotra Patera]], a feature regarded as \"the very best evidence, by far, for volcanic topography anywhere documented on an icy satellite.\"<ref name=\"NASA statement\">\"[http://saturn.jpl.nasa.gov/news/newsreleases/newsrelease20101214/ Cassini Spots Potential Ice Volcano on Saturn Moon]\". NASA, December 14, 2010</ref> Cryovolcanism is one process hypothesized to be a significant source of the methane found in Titan's atmosphere.<ref name=\"rain\">{{cite web |title=Cassini Finds Hydrocarbon Rains May Fill The Lakes |author=Media Relations Office: Cassini Imaging Central Laboratory For Operations |publisher=Space Science Institute, Boulder, Colorado |date=2009 |url=http://ciclops.org/view.php?id=5471&js=1 |accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, observations by the [[Gemini Observatory]] showing patches of ammonia hydrates and water crystals on the surface of [[Pluto]]'s moon [[Charon (moon)|Charon]] suggested the presence of active cryovolcanoes or cryogeysers.<ref name=ice>{{cite web|title=Charon: An ice machine in the ultimate deep freeze|work=Gemini Observatory|year=2007|url=http://www.spaceflightnow.com/news/n0707/17charon/|accessdate=18 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.iop.org/EJ/article/0004-637X/663/2/1406/70488.html | author=Cook | title=Near-Infrared Spectroscopy of Charon: Possible Evidence for Cryovolcanism on Kuiper Belt Objects | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | volume=663 | issue=2 | pages=1406\u20131419 | year=2007 | doi=10.1086/518222 | last2=Desch | first2=Steven J. | last3=Roush | first3=Ted L. | last4=Trujillo | first4=Chadwick A. | last5=Geballe | first5=T. R. | bibcode=2007ApJ...663.1406C|display-authors=etal| doi-access=free }}</ref> Subsequent observations by New Horizons in 2015 found that Charon has a youthful surface, supporting this idea.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beatty |first=Kelly |url=http://www.skyandtelescope.com/astronomy-news/charon-cracked-cratered-and-crazy-100220155/ |title=Charon: Cracked, Cratered, and Colorful |work=Sky and Telescope |date=2 October 2015 |accessdate=2015-10-03 }}</ref> Pluto itself has two features that have been identified as possible cryovolcanoes, being mountains with indented peaks.<ref name = \"Witze2015-11-09\">{{cite journal\n | url = http://www.nature.com/news/icy-volcanoes-may-dot-pluto-s-surface-1.18756\n | title = Icy volcanoes may dot Pluto's surface\n | last = Witze | first = A. | date = 2015-11-09 | journal = Nature News\n | doi=10.1038/nature.2015.18756 | access-date = 2015-11-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, two distinct bright spots inside a crater of the [[dwarf planet]] [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] were imaged by the ''[[Dawn (spacecraft)|Dawn]]'' spacecraft, leading to speculation about a possible cryovolcanic origin.<ref name = \"O'Neill2015.02.25\">{{cite web\n | last = O'Neill | first = I. | title = Ceres' Mystery Bright Dots May Have Volcanic Origin\n | publisher = [[Discovery Communications]]\n | date = 25 February 2015 | accessdate = 1 March 2015\n | url = http://news.discovery.com/space/ceres-mystery-bright-dots-may-have-volcanic-origin-150225.htm\n }}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\nIn September 2016, NASA JPL and NASA Goddard scientists released findings that large [[Ahuna Dome]] on Ceres is a \"volcanic dome unlike any seen elsewhere in the solar system. [The large] mountain is likely volcanic in nature. Specifically, it would be a cryovolcano -- a volcano that erupts a liquid made of volatiles such as water, instead of silicates. ... the only known example of a cryovolcano that potentially formed from a salty mud mix, and that formed in the geologically recent past.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://dawn.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news-detail.html?id=6611 | title=News}}</ref> In addition, at least some of Ceres' well known bright spots (notably including the ones in Occator crater) are likely also cryovolcanic in origin.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Ceres_The_tiny_world_where_volcanoes_erupt_ice_999.html | title=Ceres: The tiny world where volcanoes erupt ice}}</ref> A study published in March 2017 suggests that Occator's most recent large eruption occurred about 4 million years ago and thus that Ceres may still be active.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/space/solar-system/a25552/ice-volcanoes-ceres-active/ | title=The Ice Volcanoes of Ceres Were Highly Active a Few Million Years Ago| date=2017-03-06}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery |align=center\n| title  = Cryovolcanism on [[Enceladus]]\n| lines  = 2\n| width  = 250\n| height = 250\n|File:Enceladus Cold Geyser Model.svg|One possible scheme for Enceladus's cryovolcanism\n|File:PIA19059-SaturnMoon-Enceladus-OceanMethane-20150311.png|Possible origins of methane found in plumes through its subsurface ocean\n|File:Enceladus plume molecules.jpg|Chemical composition of the plumes of Enceladus\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{annotated link|List of extraterrestrial volcanoes}}\n*{{annotated link|Ice volcano}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=Lopes_2013>{{cite journal\n |author1=Lopes, R. M. C. |author2=Kirk, R. L. |author3=Mitchell, K. L. |title  = Cryovolcanism on Titan: New results from Cassini RADAR and VIMS\n |journal= Journal of Geophysical Research: Planets\n |year   = 2013\n |number = 3\n |volume = 118\n |pages  = 416\u2013435\n |doi    = 10.1002/jgre.20062\n |bibcode= 2013JGRE..118..416L\n |display-authors=etal|url= https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-00807740/file/Lopes_et_al-2013-Journal_of_Geophysical_Research__Planets.pdf\n }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nineplanets.org/triton.html Triton] - Triton at the eight Planets\n* [http://www.solarviews.com/cap/nep/triton1.htm South Pole of Triton] - Triton at SolarViews.com\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060818152154/http://www.planetary.org/news/2005/0730_Enceladus_South_Polar_Stripes_Spew.html Enceladus' South Polar Stripes Spew \"Warm\" Water] - News article at the [http://www.planetary.org Planetary Society]\n* [http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/lpsc2007/pdf/1901.pdf Cryovolcanism on Charon and other Kuiper Belt Objects]\n* [http://www.geo.mtu.edu/volcanoes/ice/ Ice Volcanoes of Lake Superior's South Shore]\n* {{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/yblog_thelookout/20110208/ts_yblog_thelookout/ice-volcanoes-are-all-the-rage-this-winter |title=Ice volcanoes are all the rage this winter: How do you stimulate a regional tourist economy? |work=The Lookout |publisher=[[Yahoo News]]\n|first1=Brett Michael |last1=Dykes |date=February 8, 2011 |accessdate=February 8, 2011}}\n* {{cite news |url=http://www.jsonline.com/news/milwaukee/115448834.html |title=Ice volcanoes attract curious explorers to Lake Michigan shore: Experts warn to explore formations with caution |first1=Karen |last1=Herzog |publisher=[[Journal Sentinel]] |date=February 6, 2011 |accessdate=February 8, 2011}}\n\n{{Volcanoes}}\n\n[[Category:Volcanology]]\n[[Category:Planetary geology]]\n", "name_user": "The High Fin Sperm Whale", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eObservations:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryovolcano"}
{"title_page": "Jeff Teague (automotive designer)", "text_new": "{{For|the basketball player Jeff Teague|Jeff Teague (basketball)}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Jeffrey W. Teague\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1956|10|3}}\n| birth_place = .\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|2016|7|29|1956|10|3}}\n| death_place = [[Agoura Hills, California]], U.S.\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = [[Automotive design]]er \n}}\n\n'''Jeff Teague''' (1956-2016) was an [[Americans|American]] [[automotive design]]er and design consultant for [[Volkswagen]], [[Ford Motor Company]], [[Mitsubishi Motors]], [[Hyundai Motor Group]] and [[Kia Motors]] &mdash; known widely for his role as principal designer of the 1983-1992 [[Lincoln Mark VII]]. \n\nTeague founded the Transportation Design Department at the [[Academy of Art University]] (formerly Academy of Art College) in San Francisco. His father was noted industrial and automotive designer, [[Richard A. Teague|Dick Teague]]. \n\n== Background ==\nTeague was born in Franklin, Michigan to Marian Rose Teague and [[Richard A. Teague]].  His father was renowned as an industrial designer and as a car designer, notably with [[American Motors Corporation]] where his work included the [[AMC Gremlin]], [[AMC AMX|AMX]], [[AMC Hornet|Hornet]] and [[AMC Pacer|Pacer]], as well as the [[Jeep Cherokee (XJ)]].\n\nTeague attended Groves High School and graduated from the [[Art Center College of Design]] in Pasadena California in 1978. He died unexpectedly in 2016, survived by his mother, Marian Rose Teague; wife Glenda Gillery Teague and three children; Rachel, Thea Nicole (Nikki) and Authur Jeffrey Teague (AJ).\n\n== Career and design work ==\nTeague became a designer after school with Ford Motor Corporation in Dearborn Michigan, was a senior designer with [[Mitsubishi Motors North America]] in Cypress California, was Chief Designer Volkswagen AG of Germany in Wolfsburg, Germany, and Studio Chief for Volkswagen of America<ref name=\"ref5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Celebrate the Life and Design of Jeff Teague\n |publisher    = Autodesigno\n |author       = \n |date         = August 2, 2016\n |url          = https://autodesigno.com/jeff-teague-a-celebration-of-life-and-design/}}</ref> He was subsequently the senior designer at [[Mitsubishi Motors]] of America in Simi Valley California, and later was design consultant with [[Hyundai Motor Group|Hyundai]] and [[Kia Motors|Kia]].\n\n[[File:1984-1985 Lincoln Continental Mark VII.jpg|thumb|1983-92 Lincoln Mark VII]]\nWhile working at [[Ford Motor Company]], Teague worked under [[Jack Telnack]] on designs for the 1983 Ford Thunderbird, the seventh generation (1982\u20131987) [[Lincoln Continental#Seventh generation (1982\u20131987)|Lincoln Continental]] and the wagon variants of the first generation [[Ford Taurus]] and [[Mercury Sable]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.smartfellowspress.com/killing_the_goose_21.htm |last=Garrison |first=Jasper |title=Killing the Goose... Chapter 21: Taurus |date=2003 |publisher=Smart Fellows Press |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120205003020/http://www.smartfellowspress.com/killing_the_goose_21.htm |archivedate=5 February 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref> He was the principal designer for the 1983-1992 [[Lincoln Mark VII]].\n\nIn 1998, Teague started a design program in Automotive and Industrial design at the [[Academy of Art University]] (formerly Academy of Art College) in San Francisco. Teague hired and managed a multi-cultural international staff and developed the program curriculum and syllabus, later serving on the the Board of Directors until his death in 2016.\n\nTeague provided design services and consulting services to [[Hyundai Motor Group|Hyundai]], [[Kia Motors|Kia]], [[Subaru]], and others. He now heads his own firm: Teague Design<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=105333 |publisher=Edmund's Inside Line |title=Duesenberg May Hit the Streets Again |archivedate=18 April 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050418223340/http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId%3D105333 |accessdate=20 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He started the company in 1998 in [[Agoura Hills, California]], and it was incorporated in 2000.\n\nHe designed an updated ''AMX 4'' based on AMC's mid-engine sports car that contributed to his father's design reputation.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.teaguedesigninc.com/AMX-4.html |publisher=Teague Design |title=AMX3 / AMX4 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120508225717/http://www.teaguedesigninc.com/AMX-4.html |archivedate=8 May 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2006, Teague provided design services for the revival [[Duesenberg]] line of automobiles.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.businessweek.com/autos/content/jan2006/bw20060131_605519.htm |journal=Business Week |title=Duesenberg Rises Again |first=Reena |last=Jana |date=1 February 2006 |accessdate=19 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523144452/http://www.businessweek.com/autos/content/jan2006/bw20060131_605519.htm |archivedate=23 May 2012 }}</ref> The new design of the ''Duesenberg II Torpedo Coupe'' was delayed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2007/09/26/duesenberg-revival-delayed/ |title=Duesenberg revival delayed |first=Dan |last=Roth |date=26 September 2007 |accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref> He is Chief Design Director for the new [[Baldwin, Wisconsin]], company and the car was expected to be introduced in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.duesenbergcustomcoach.com/torpedocoupe.html |title=Duesenberg Torpedo Coupe |publisher=Duesenberg Motors |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120107122102/http://duesenbergcustomcoach.com/torpedocoupe.html |archivedate=7 January 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref> In 2012, the company bought a building in Baldwin to produce its replica cars on a modern Ford chassis, as well as a [[motorized tricycle]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.twincities.com/ci_19989661 |title=Duesenberg Motors' replica cars to be made in Baldwin, Wis. |first=Andy |last=Rathbun |publisher=Pioneer Press |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nJeff Teague died on July 29, 2016 at his home in [[Agoura Hills, California]], at age 59.<ref name=\"hemmings\">{{cite web|publisher=Hemmings Motor News |title=Designer Jeff Teague, Son of Dick Teague, dies at 59 |accessdate=2018-12-19 |url=https://www.hemmings.com/blog/2016/08/05/designer-jeff-teague-son-of-dick-teague-dies-at-59/ }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Jeff Teague interview by ASME: {{cite web|url= https://www.asme.org/engineering-topics/articles/automotive-design/car-designing-past-and-present |title= Car Designing: Past and Present |date=January 2012 |first=Eric |last=Butterman |publisher=American Society of Mechanical Engineers ASME |accessdate=20 April 2015}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teague, Jeff}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Art Center College of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:American automobile designers]]\n[[Category:American Motors people]]\n[[Category:Mitsubishi Motors people]]\n[[Category:Ford designers]]\n[[Category:People from Agoura Hills, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the basketball player Jeff Teague|Jeff Teague (basketball)}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Jeffrey W. Teague\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1956|10|3}}\n| birth_place = .\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|2016|7|29|1956|10|3}}\n| death_place = [[Agoura Hills, California]], U.S.\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = [[Automotive design]]er \n}}\n\n'''Jeff Teague''' (1956-2016) was an [[Americans|American]] [[automotive design]]er and design consultant for [[Volkswagen]], [[Ford Motor Company]], [[Mitsubishi Motors]], [[Hyundai Motor Group]] and [[Kia Motors]] &mdash; known widely for his role as principal designer of the 1983-1992 [[Lincoln Mark VII]]. \n\nTeague founded the Transportation Design Department at the [[Academy of Art University]] (formerly Academy of Art College) in San Francisco. His father was noted industrial and automotive designer [[Richard A. Teague|Dick Teague]]. \n\n== Background ==\nTeague was born in Franklin, Michigan to Marian Rose Teague and [[Richard A. Teague]].  His father was renowned as an industrial designer and as a car designer, notably with [[American Motors Corporation]] where his work included the [[AMC Gremlin]], [[AMC AMX|AMX]], [[AMC Hornet|Hornet]] and [[AMC Pacer|Pacer]], as well as the [[Jeep Cherokee (XJ)]].\n\nTeague attended Groves High School and graduated from the [[Art Center College of Design]] in Pasadena California in 1978. He died unexpectedly in 2016, survived by his mother, Marian Rose Teague; wife Glenda Gillery Teague and three children; Rachel, Thea Nicole (Nikki) and Authur Jeffrey Teague (AJ).\n\n== Career and design work ==\nTeague became a designer after school with Ford Motor Corporation in Dearborn Michigan, was a senior designer with [[Mitsubishi Motors North America]] in Cypress California, was Chief Designer Volkswagen AG of Germany in Wolfsburg, Germany, and Studio Chief for Volkswagen of America<ref name=\"ref5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Celebrate the Life and Design of Jeff Teague\n |publisher    = Autodesigno\n |author       = \n |date         = August 2, 2016\n |url          = https://autodesigno.com/jeff-teague-a-celebration-of-life-and-design/}}</ref> He was subsequently the senior designer at [[Mitsubishi Motors]] of America in Simi Valley California, and later was design consultant with [[Hyundai Motor Group|Hyundai]] and [[Kia Motors|Kia]].\n\n[[File:1984-1985 Lincoln Continental Mark VII.jpg|thumb|1983-92 Lincoln Mark VII]]\nWhile working at [[Ford Motor Company]], Teague worked under [[Jack Telnack]] on designs for the 1983 Ford Thunderbird, the seventh generation (1982\u20131987) [[Lincoln Continental#Seventh generation (1982\u20131987)|Lincoln Continental]] and the wagon variants of the first generation [[Ford Taurus]] and [[Mercury Sable]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.smartfellowspress.com/killing_the_goose_21.htm |last=Garrison |first=Jasper |title=Killing the Goose... Chapter 21: Taurus |date=2003 |publisher=Smart Fellows Press |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120205003020/http://www.smartfellowspress.com/killing_the_goose_21.htm |archivedate=5 February 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref> He was the principal designer for the 1983-1992 [[Lincoln Mark VII]].\n\nIn 1998, Teague started a design program in Automotive and Industrial design at the [[Academy of Art University]] (formerly Academy of Art College) in San Francisco. Teague hired and managed a multi-cultural international staff and developed the program curriculum and syllabus, later serving on the the Board of Directors until his death in 2016.\n\nTeague provided design services and consulting services to [[Hyundai Motor Group|Hyundai]], [[Kia Motors|Kia]], [[Subaru]], and others. He now heads his own firm: Teague Design<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=105333 |publisher=Edmund's Inside Line |title=Duesenberg May Hit the Streets Again |archivedate=18 April 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050418223340/http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId%3D105333 |accessdate=20 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He started the company in 1998 in [[Agoura Hills, California]], and it was incorporated in 2000.\n\nHe designed an updated ''AMX 4'' based on AMC's mid-engine sports car that contributed to his father's design reputation.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.teaguedesigninc.com/AMX-4.html |publisher=Teague Design |title=AMX3 / AMX4 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120508225717/http://www.teaguedesigninc.com/AMX-4.html |archivedate=8 May 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2006, Teague provided design services for the revival [[Duesenberg]] line of automobiles.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.businessweek.com/autos/content/jan2006/bw20060131_605519.htm |journal=Business Week |title=Duesenberg Rises Again |first=Reena |last=Jana |date=1 February 2006 |accessdate=19 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523144452/http://www.businessweek.com/autos/content/jan2006/bw20060131_605519.htm |archivedate=23 May 2012 }}</ref> The new design of the ''Duesenberg II Torpedo Coupe'' was delayed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2007/09/26/duesenberg-revival-delayed/ |title=Duesenberg revival delayed |first=Dan |last=Roth |date=26 September 2007 |accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref> He is Chief Design Director for the new [[Baldwin, Wisconsin]], company and the car was expected to be introduced in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.duesenbergcustomcoach.com/torpedocoupe.html |title=Duesenberg Torpedo Coupe |publisher=Duesenberg Motors |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120107122102/http://duesenbergcustomcoach.com/torpedocoupe.html |archivedate=7 January 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref> In 2012, the company bought a building in Baldwin to produce its replica cars on a modern Ford chassis, as well as a [[motorized tricycle]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.twincities.com/ci_19989661 |title=Duesenberg Motors' replica cars to be made in Baldwin, Wis. |first=Andy |last=Rathbun |publisher=Pioneer Press |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nJeff Teague died on July 29, 2016 at his home in [[Agoura Hills, California]], at age 59.<ref name=\"hemmings\">{{cite web|publisher=Hemmings Motor News |title=Designer Jeff Teague, Son of Dick Teague, dies at 59 |accessdate=2018-12-19 |url=https://www.hemmings.com/blog/2016/08/05/designer-jeff-teague-son-of-dick-teague-dies-at-59/ }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Jeff Teague interview by ASME: {{cite web|url= https://www.asme.org/engineering-topics/articles/automotive-design/car-designing-past-and-present |title= Car Designing: Past and Present |date=January 2012 |first=Eric |last=Butterman |publisher=American Society of Mechanical Engineers ASME |accessdate=20 April 2015}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teague, Jeff}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Art Center College of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:American automobile designers]]\n[[Category:American Motors people]]\n[[Category:Mitsubishi Motors people]]\n[[Category:Ford designers]]\n[[Category:People from Agoura Hills, California]]\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_Teague_(automotive_designer)"}
{"title_page": "As the Stomach Turns", "text_new": "'''\"As the Stomach Turns\"''' is a series of [[sketch comedy|comedy sketches]] parodying the [[soap opera]] ''[[As the World Turns]]'' (or its title, at any rate) featured on ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]'', with one installment airing on ''[[Carol Burnett & Company]]''. The sketch was created by show writers Kenny Solms and [[Gail Parent]].<ref>{{cite interview |last=Burnett |first=Carol |subjectlink= |interviewer=Carol Burnett Show: The Lost Episodes Limited Edition (7 DVD Collection) |title=Featurette: Fabulous Firsts |url= |date= |work=Carol Burnett Show: The Lost Episodes Limited Edition (7 DVD Collection) }}</ref> ''The Carol Burnett Show'' introduced the series during its first season in 1967\u201368 and continued to air new installments for the remainder of its 11-season run, through its final season in 1977\u201378. However, the final installment of \"As the Stomach Turns\" would not air until September 8, 1979, on a different four-week summer series titled ''Carol Burnett & Company''. This was the only installment of \"As the Stomach Turns\" that did not air on ''The Carol Burnett Show'' which had completed its run almost a year and a half earlier on March 29, 1978.\n\n==Premise==\nThe sketch's premise was to describe, in great detail, the problems of a woman in her 30s named Marion Clayton (played by [[Carol Burnett]]), who lived in the fictional town of Canoga Falls. The first installment aired on the 21st episode of the first season on February 12, 1968.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0536556|title=The Carol Burnett Show (1967\u20131978) Episode #1.21 |author= IMDB|date=|website=|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref> As introduced by [[Lyle Waggoner]], it was supposed to be the final episode of a 15-year long soap opera.<ref>{{cite episode |title=022 |series=The Carol Burnett Show |network=[[CBS]] |date=February 12, 1968}}</ref>\n\nThe sketch dealt with problems that were more likely to be seen on a soap opera than in real life, although many skits were inspired by popular television shows or movies. An example of the latter was when Marion's niece Raven (played by [[Bernadette Peters]] in a guest spot) came to visit her and was possessed by a devil, Marion assumed, because Raven was such a nice girl normally. Otto Blackflag, the town exterminator, now styling himself as a freelance exorcist (played by [[Tim Conway]] and  using the same faux-Swedish dialect that he would use to play the character [[Mrs. Wiggins|Mr. Tudball]]) exorcised the demon from Raven's body. This same sort of plot was eventually done, in all seriousness, on ''[[Days of Our Lives]]'' decades later.\n\nAnother movie parody saw Marion meet the bedraggled \"Richard Dryface,\" played by guest [[Steve Martin]] in a spoof of ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]'', complete with a grey, bulbous-headed alien played by Conway.\n\nThe sketch also touched on stereotypical aspects of production values in American soaps. Many times, Marion forgot what she wanted to say, reminiscent of the times when soap operas were broadcast live and actors routinely forgot their next line. Marion also answered the door either too soon or too late when someone rang her doorbell. Other times, she would miss the correct time to answer the phone, saying \"Hello\" before the sound effect came for it to ring. On live soap opera productions, these were big problems; due to the live nature of the show, they happened fairly frequently, and were subsequently spoofed at length on ''The Carol Burnett Show''.\n\nIn addition to the missed cues, the sketch was notorious for overusing loud and plangent [[Organ (music)|organ music]], a reference to a time when soap operas would have in-house organists play dramatic music as well as the show's theme song (when this skit first ran, organ music was still in wide use on the serials). Organ music was eventually discontinued in the mid-1970s, around the time ''The Carol Burnett Show'' wrapped up its run, so when the sketch is seen in syndication today, it brings back a sense of production technique that is now seen by many younger soap viewers as archaic and outdated.\n\nOne of the sketch's recurring characters is Marion's \"ne'er-do-well\" daughter (played by [[Vicki Lawrence]]) who arrives at the door holding a baby (a doll), usually says \"Don't you recognize me mother? I'm your daughter,\" then leaves after giving the baby to Marion who immediately stashes it in the umbrella stand.<ref name=\"emmytvlegends.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/vicki-lawrence#|title=Vicki Lawrence|work=Archive of American Television|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref> This was a parody of the fact that traditional soap operas have little use for child characters, either dropping them from the plot line shortly after they are introduced or [[Soap Opera Rapid Aging Syndrome|unnaturally aging]] them into adulthood or, more recently, into the teenage years (for example, a young character might be sent upstairs to put on his or her shoes and never be referred to again).\n\nThe sketch also marks the first appearances of [[Harvey Korman]]'s Mother Marcus character, who had also become a recurring resident of Canoga Falls, as well as [[Tim Conway]]'s [[The Oldest Man (character)|oldest man character]], who within the confines of the series played several characters, including Marion's grandfather, her Uncle Waldo, insurance agent Duane Toddleberry, and obscene phone caller Marvin Peterson, Jr.<ref>{{cite interview |last=Burnett |first=Carol |subjectlink= |interviewer=Carol Burnett Show: The Lost Episodes Limited Edition (7 DVD Collection) |title=Featurette: Fabulous Firsts |url= |date= |work=Carol Burnett Show: The Lost Episodes Limited Edition (7 DVD Collection) }}</ref>\n\nThe sketch was famous for the parody ending in which the announcer would ask foreboding, progressively nonsensical questions about the characters while focusing on their puzzled reactions.\n\n==Trivia==\n* In her 1996 memoir, \"As My World Still Turns\", actress [[Eileen Fulton]], who has starred on the [[CBS]] soap ''[[As the World Turns]]'' for over four decades, claimed credit for coming up with the concept for \"As the Stomach Turns\".  Fulton stated that when she was contacted to be a guest star on the ''Burnett'' show, she suggested a parody of a soap called \"As the Stomach Turns\".  Ultimately Fulton ended up not appearing on the ''Burnett'' show, but the \"Stomach Turns\" sketch did.<ref>{{cite book|title= As My World Still Turns|last= Fulton|first= Eileen|authorlink= |author2= Atholl, Desmond|author3= Cherkinian, Michael|year= 1996|publisher= [[St. Martin's Press]]|location= [[New York City|New York]]|isbn= 1-55972-274-6|oclc= 31606927|pages= |url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/asmyworldstilltu00fult}}</ref>\n* [[Cher]] appeared on an episode of \"As the Stomach Turns\" as Pocahontas Pirelli, \"the town half-breed: half-Indian, and half-dressed,\" which was a play on her hit song of the time, \"[[Half-Breed (song)|Half-Breed]].\" She came in wearing a Native American headdress and a bikini top.\n* In an early sketch, Carol Burnett opens the door to find Harvey Korman as Mother Marcus for the character's first appearance on the show. When rehearsing the sketch, Korman never appeared in costume but spoke in the voice. When Burnett opened the door in dress rehearsal it was the first time she had actually seen him dressed up as the character. Burnett's reaction (pausing, struggling to regain her composure before slamming the door in his face, then cracking up when she opened the door again to move the script along) was completely genuine.\n\n==Sketches==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | N\u00ba\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Episode\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Airdate\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Title & Description\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Guest stars\n|-\n| 1\n| Season 1 (1967\u201368)\n| Ep 21\n| February 12, 1968\n| Marion's friend Victoria's long lost son is found after 15 years.\n| [[Martha Raye]], [[Betty Grable]]\n|-\n| 2\n| Season 2 (1968\u201369)\n| Ep 6\n| November 4, 1968\n| Marion and her widow friend Laura come back from a funeral.\n| [[Lucille Ball]], [[Eddie Albert]], [[Nancy Wilson (jazz singer)|Nancy Wilson]]\n|-\n| 3\n| rowspan=2 | Season 3 (1969\u201370)\n| Ep 5\n| October 20, 1969\n| Marion is planning on sending her grandfather away to Sun City.\n| [[Tim Conway]], [[Ken Berry]]\n|-\n| 4\n| Ep 6\n| November 3, 1969\n| Marion's brother Teddy comes for a visit and announces he's engaged to Miss Lily, the \"town naughty lady\".\n| [[Gwen Verdon]], [[Pat Boone]]\n|-\n| 5\n| rowspan=4 | Season 4 (1970\u201371)\n| Ep 3\n| September 28, 1970\n| Marion's friend Joyce announces she's a kleptomaniac.\n| [[Nanette Fabray]], [[Nancy Wilson (jazz singer)|Nancy Wilson]]\n|-\n| 6\n| Ep 11\n| November 23, 1970\n| Marion's rich friend Louise and the Canoga Twins come over for a visit.\n| [[Dyan Cannon]], [[Paul Lynde]]\n|-\n| 7\n| Ep 21\n| February 15, 1971\n| Marion's friend Estelle announces she's a werewolf.\n| [[Totie Fields]]\n|-\n| 8\n| Ep 26\n| March 29, 1971\n| Marion tells her friend Ren\u00e9e that she is broke and Felix Murdock the banker comes to foreclose on her house.\n| [[Nanette Fabray]], [[Paul Lynde]]\n|-\n| 9\n| rowspan=3 | Season 5 (1971\u201372)\n| Ep 3\n| October 6, 1971\n| Marion's friend Jinx Vandenberg suffers from bad luck.\n| [[Carol Channing]], [[Steve Lawrence]]\n|-\n| 10\n| Ep 7\n| November 3, 1971\n| Marion's visitors are town masochist Mel Torment and Mother Marcus.\n| [[Bing Crosby]], [[Paul Lynde]]\n|-\n| 11\n| Ep 8\n| November 10, 1971\n| Marion's modelling friend Suzie Shrimpton comes back to Canoga Falls.\n| [[Bernadette Peters]], [[Cass Elliot]]\n|-\n| 12\n| rowspan=2 | Season 6 (1972\u201373)\n| Ep 8\n| November 1, 1972\n| Marion goes to the circus.\n| [[Jerry Stiller]], [[Anne Meara]]\n|-\n| 13\n| Ep 20\n| February 17, 1973\n| Marion's friend David is deathly afraid of women.\n| [[Valerie Harper]], [[Tim Conway]]\n|-\n| 14\n| rowspan=2 | Season 7 (1973\u201374)\n| Ep 9\n| November 10, 1973\n| While desperately seeking a problem, Marion meets her long-lost twin sister.\n| [[Petula Clark]]\n|-\n| 15\n| Ep 20\n| February 16, 1974\n| Marion's niece Raven is possessed by the devil.\n| [[Bernadette Peters]]\n|-\n| 16\n| Season 8 (1974\u201375)\n| Ep 11\n| December 7, 1974\n| Don Provolone comes to blackmail Marion.\n| [[Steve Lawrence]]\n|-\n| 17\n| Season 9 (1975\u201376)\n| Ep 3\n| September 27, 1975\n| Pocahontas Perrelli visits and Canoga Falls has a new hairdresser, Warren Pretty \n| [[Cher]]\n|-\n| 18\n| Season 10 (1976\u201377)\n| Ep 20\n| February 26, 1977\n| Marion comes back from her daughter Jamie's funeral, only to realize that she's not dead but [[The Bionic Woman|bionic]].\n| N/A\n|-\n| 19\n| Season 11 (1977\u201378)\n| Ep 21\n| March 5, 1978\n| Marion's daughter comes back to Canoga Falls with an alien.\n| [[Steve Martin]], [[Betty White]]\n|-\n| 20\n| ''[[Carol Burnett & Company]]''\n| Ep 1.4\n| September 8, 1979\n| Marion is surprised by a visit from Pamela, a former \"Miss America\" pageant winner who refuses to give up her crown.\n| [[Sally Field]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Carol Burnett Show}}\n\n[[Category:Comedy sketches]]\n[[Category:Television soap opera parodies]]\n[[Category:Carol Burnett]]\n", "text_old": "'''\"As the Stomach Turns\"''' is a series of [[sketch comedy|comedy sketches]] parodying the [[soap opera]] ''[[As the World Turns]]'' (or its title, at any rate) featured on ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]'', with one installment airing on ''[[Carol Burnett & Company]]''. The sketch was created by show writers Kenny Solms and [[Gail Parent]].<ref>{{cite interview |last=Burnett |first=Carol |subjectlink= |interviewer=Carol Burnett Show: The Lost Episodes Limited Edition (7 DVD Collection) |title=Featurette: Fabulous Firsts |url= |date= |work=Carol Burnett Show: The Lost Episodes Limited Edition (7 DVD Collection) }}</ref> ''The Carol Burnett Show'' introduced the series during its first season in 1967\u201368 and continued to air new installments for the remainder of its 11-season run, through its final season in 1977\u201378. However, the final installment of \"As the Stomach Turns\" would not air until September 8, 1979, on a different four-week summer series titled ''Carol Burnett & Company''. This was the only installment of \"As the Stomach Turns\" that did not air on ''The Carol Burnett Show'' which had completed its run almost a year and a half earlier on March 29, 1978.\n\n==Premise==\nThe sketch's premise was to describe, in great detail, the problems of a woman in her 30s named Marion Clayton (played by [[Carol Burnett]]), who lived in the fictional town of Canoga Falls. The first installment aired on the 21st episode of the first season on February 12, 1968.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0536556|title=The Carol Burnett Show (1967\u20131978) Episode #1.21 |author= IMDB|date=|website=|accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref> As introduced by [[Lyle Waggoner]], it was supposed to be the final episode of a 15-year long soap opera.<ref>{{cite episode |title=022 |series=The Carol Burnett Show |network=[[CBS]] |date=February 12, 1968}}</ref>\n\nThe sketch dealt with problems that were more likely to be seen on a soap opera than in real life, although many skits were inspired by popular television shows or movies. An example of the latter was when Marion's niece Raven (played by [[Bernadette Peters]] in a guest spot) came to visit her and was possessed by a devil, Marion assumed, because Raven was such a nice girl normally. Otto Blackflag, the town exterminator, now styling himself as a freelance exorcist (played by [[Tim Conway]] and  using the same faux-Swedish dialect that he would